<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Agent May Head NJ State Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A veteran FBI agent has been picked to head  
the New Jersey State Police, an embattled 2,700-member force 
accused of targeting minority drivers for traffic stops and 
discriminating against its own officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Christie Whitman announced her choice of Carson Dunbar Jr.  
on Monday. His nomination will be considered by state lawmakers 
next Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunbar, 47, who is black, would be the first minority to head  
the agency. The former New Jersey state trooper who now heads the 
FBI's New York field office acknowledged he faces a difficult task. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do I feel a little pressure?'' he said. ``Yeah. I feel a lot  
of pressure ... I have enough confidence that the State Police will 
change itself. The only thing that I can provide is direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dunbar also said he understands the worries of minority  
motorists who fear being pulled over because of their race, adding 
that he believes that has happened to him. 
</P>
<P>
	The attorney general's office has issued a report documenting  
racial profiling among units patrolling the New Jersey Turnpike. 
Attorney General John Farmer has called for new procedures and 
training for traffic stops and searches, as well as offices to 
receive civilian complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunbar would replace Col. Carl Williams, who was fired in  
February when published remarks appeared in which he linked 
minorities to the major volume of drug traffic. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
