<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft To Make Final Arguments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the weeks before the start of the Microsoft  
Corp. antitrust trial, the company's lawyer elicited a surprisingly 
candid admission from the government's top economics expert. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft lawyer Michael Lacovara challenged economist Franklin  
Fisher last September over claims that the company held monopoly 
power because its Windows software was effectively the only viable 
operating system for computers. Weren't there others? 
</P>
<P>
	``Apple, Unix,'' Fisher answered. ``There are a couple of other  
minor ones. Is Linux an operating system? I can't remember.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The exchange was remarkable as one illustration of how quickly  
the fast-paced technology industry has changed since the Justice 
Department and 19 states filed the lawsuit against Microsoft. It 
has left some experts wondering how to apply U.S. antitrust laws 
fairly -- in cases where trials can take years -- to an industry 
frequently described as moving in compressed ``Internet time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Linux, which barely drew recognition from Fisher in September,  
is now the darling of technology pundits and a product offered by a 
few of the nation's largest computer makers alongside Windows. And 
Microsoft points to the extraordinary financial success of Red Hat 
Inc., a leading Linux vendor whose stock soared from $14 on its 
first day trading last month to close Monday at $110.47. 
</P>
<P>
	``This case is moving along at a breakneck speed in antitrust  
terms,'' said William Kovacic, an antitrust expert at George 
Washington University. ``Yet the end result may come well after 
intervening events have rendered the case less important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft and the government returned today for closing  
arguments in the trial, the final time lawyers will meet in the 
courtroom prior to U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's 
first of a two-phase verdict. That decision could come as early as 
next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Houck of the New York attorney general's office told the  
judge that Microsoft wields an ``unshakable stranglehold'' on the 
high-tech industry because of the dominance of its Windows 
operating system. ``No company has been able to make a dent in that 
market in a decade,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department lawyer David Boies used the company's own  
words against it in the second part of the government's closing 
arguments, continually referring to dozens of internal E-mail 
messages from Microsoft executives and the videotaped deposition of 
its billionaire chairman, Bill Gates. 
</P>
<P>
	Houck described this as ``done-in by your own exhibit'' of  
evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft lawyers were making their final arguments later in the  
day. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the sides planned to summarize the arguments each  
has tried to construct through 76 days of testimony, since the 
case's opening salvo last October. 
</P>
<P>
	Much has changed since then: America Online Inc. bought Netscape  
Communications Corp. for $10 billion, aligning two of Microsoft's 
biggest rivals on the Internet. High-speed Internet connections are 
much more common, making it easier to download software and even 
run so-called ``server-based'' computer programs across the 
Internet that don't require any particular operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft said those changes undermine the case against it,  
though government lawyers point to today's market reality as proof 
Microsoft wields monopoly power: It's still nearly impossible to 
buy a computer these days without the company's software already 
loaded. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the trial's players have changed. John Rose, a senior  
executive at Compaq Computer Corp. who testified for Microsoft, was 
unceremoniously fired in a management shakeup. Microsoft's Paul 
Maritz, who testified as the executive in charge of Windows, now 
spends his time working with outside software developers at the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	And although the government's case focused partly on Microsoft's  
decision to include its Internet software in Windows 98, the next 
version of its software is likely to ship before any final verdict 
and the anticipated appeals process. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look out over the horizon ... I don't see a final  
decision by the Supreme Court until the middle of 2002,'' Kovacic 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft said it planned in closing arguments to reject  
allegations that it illegally wields monopoly power over the 
software that runs most of the world's personal computers, 
according to a company lawyer, who asked not to be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft also indicated it will deny that it ever misused its  
influence to crush rivals that it believed posed a threat to its 
lucrative Windows software, such as the Internet browser developed 
by the former Netscape. 
</P>
<P>
	In its most recent court papers, Microsoft argued that the  
government improperly considered only operating system software for 
IBM-type computers when it defined the company's large share of 
that market. But the government more widely considered other 
technologies, such as Internet software, when it sought to portray 
Microsoft as a bully toward rivals, the lawyer said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
