<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cruise Ship in Safer Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A cruise ship carrying 1,700 people headed  
slowly home today after an engine fire left it adrift in rough seas 
in the Gulf of Mexico and Tropical Storm Harvey forced a long 
detour. 
</P>
<P>
	The 660-foot Tropicale was disabled by a fire in the engine room  
Sunday evening. The fire was extinguished quickly, but the ship was 
left without power, delaying its return to the Port of Tampa. 
</P>
<P>
	The return of the Carnival Cruise Lines ship was further delayed  
when the port closed because of Harvey, which threatened 3- to 
8-foot storm surges in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm turned south late Monday, sparing much of the area,  
and the port reopened this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tropicale completed ``a big, wide loop'' in the Gulf today  
and was heading back to Tampa at about 9 mph, Carnival spokesman 
Tim Gallagher said. The line's ships usually travel 16 mph to 20 
mph. 
</P>
<P>
	The ship, using one engine, was expected to reach Tampa by  
Wednesday. It was experiencing about nine-foot seas, no problem for 
a ship longer than two football fields, Gallagher said. 
</P>
<P>
	A tug boat, the Beverly Anderson, was following the ship.  
</P>
<P>
	At midday, Harvey's poorly defined center was roughly 70 miles  
southwest of Fort Myers. Tropical storm force winds of at least 39 
mph extended 115 miles, mainly to the east of the center and away 
from the ship. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, winds whipped up to 50 mph and seas swelled to 12  
feet as the vessel drifted. Ship engineers restarted the starboard 
engine just before 4 p.m. Monday, and the Tropicale began its slow 
move out of stormy waters. 
</P>
<P>
	As a precaution, a 40-year-old man with a heart condition was  
airlifted from the ship early Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The ship still had air conditioning, working toilets and  
electricity for guest rooms. Throughout Monday, Gallagher said 
passengers were playing indoor games and getting plenty to eat. 
</P>
<P>
	The ship departed Tampa Thursday for a four-day cruise. It made  
stops in Key West and Cozumel, Mexico, and was to return to Tampa 
on Monday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	All the passengers will get a full refund and a free ticket for  
a future cruise, Gallagher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the Tropicale reaches port, the Coast Guard will begin an  
investigation to determine the case of the fire. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
