<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Plays Vs. Mets Despite Hand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Brian Jordan, bothered by a sore right hand, did  
not start Tuesday for the Atlanta Braves but did play in the opener 
of a key three-game series against the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan entered the game in the eighth inning as a pinch hitter.  
He walked and stole second, then remained on the field in the ninth 
to play right. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves won 2-1 on a pair of solo homers by Chipper Jones,  
extending their NL East lead over the second-place Mets to two 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	An examination earlier Tuesday shed no new light on Jordan's  
injury, which apparently involves a bone chip. He plans to play as 
much as possible and hold off on surgery until after the season. 
</P>
<P>
	With Jordan starting out on the bench, Atlanta shifted Gerald  
Williams to right field, putting Ryan Klesko in left and Randall 
Simon at first. Klesko filled Jordan's cleanup spot in the order 
and went 1-for-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, who leads the Braves with 106 RBIs, was initially hit on  
the right hand by Montreal's Mike Thurman on June 22. The pain has 
worsened in recent weeks, sending Jordan into a prolonged slump. 
</P>
<P>
	He is hitting only .135 (7-for-52) since Sept. 3 and has gone  
104 at-bats since his last homer on Aug. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	After sitting out Sunday's game against Montreal, Jordan took  
batting practice Tuesday and hoped to play. Instead, manager Bobby 
Cox decided to keep his right-handed outfielder on the bench with 
the Mets starting right-hander Rick Reed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was up to me, I'd try to play and go for it,'' Jordan  
said before the game. ``But it's up to Bobby now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves and Mets will meet five more times over the final 11  
games of the regular season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
