<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Tokyo Stocks Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar plunged against the yen today after the  
Bank of Japan unexpectedly announced that it would not ease 
monetary policy. Tokyo stocks closed higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 105.42 yen at 5:00 p.m. (4 a.m. EDT), down  
2.50 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and below its late New York 
level of 106.38 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 357.53  
points, or 2.04 percent, to close the day's trading at 17,932.79. 
On Monday, the average closed up 232.99 points, or 1.34 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the greenback nose-dived after the central  
bank decided in a key meeting to leave its monetary policy 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	This took financial markets by surprise, as many had predicted  
the bank would opt for an easing in a bid to halt the yen's against 
the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a statement, the bank said that funds are already  
adequate in the financial markets and that the central bank mustn't 
take policy action just because markets expect such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback had also been under selling pressure earlier in  
the day amid speculation that Japan and the United States failed to 
reach an agreement on foreign exchange policy during talks last 
week in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Zembei Mizoguchi, head of the international bureau at  
the Ministry of Finance, denied the rumors today. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuroda, who met with U.S. Undersecretary of the Treasury for  
International Affairs Timothy Geithner and other officials, has not 
disclosed what was discussed. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts believe Japan requested U.S. aid in combating the yen's  
appreciation against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices closed higher as traders awaited the  
BOJ's decision on monetary policy. The market closed before the 
announcement was made. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had said a decision to ease monetary policy could curb  
upward pressure on the yen a boon for Japan's exporters if it 
helped lower long term interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower rates would make yen-denominated assets, such as bonds,  
less attractive to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	A weaker yen, in turn, is seen as beneficial for big exporting  
companies because it makes their products more cost competitive 
abroad and raises the value of their repatriated earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 561.76 million shares changed hands on the first  
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, up from 534.19 million shares 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Decliners outnumbered advancers 640 to 574, while 129 issues  
were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section gained 10.05 points, or 0.66 percent, to 1,529.33. 
The TOPIX closed up 18.01 points, or 1.20 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average closed  
at 10,823.90 points, up 20.27. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 110.79 yen, down  
from 112.55 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.6700 percent from Monday's finish of 1.6500 percent. Its price 
fell 0.18 point to 101.75. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
