<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Fall on Weak Dollar / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices retreated again Tuesday as the  
dollar sank for a second session, falling back toward last week's 
3 1/2-year low against the Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 5/16  
point, or $3.12 1/2 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 6.09 percent from 6.07 percent 
on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged to 1/16 point lower, while intermediate maturities 
fell 1/8 to 5/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds struggled as the dollar fell broadly against other  
currencies, pressured by a report showing another huge U.S. trade 
and news that the Bank of Japan wouldn't change its money-supply 
policy to halt the yen's rise. 
</P>
<P>
	A falling dollar makes the return on U.S. investments such as  
Treasury bonds less appealing to foreign investors who convert 
their gains to other currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Tuesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
fell to 4.77 percent, down from 4.79 percent in Monday's auction. 
The discount fell 0.01 percentage point to 4.65 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields fell to 5.05 percent with a discount of 4.85  
percent, down 0.01 percentage point. One-year yields slipped to 
5.23 percent as the discount fell to 4.96 percent, both down 0.01 
percentage point from Monday's levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 5.06 percent from late Monday's 5.19 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/2 point to 112 13/32. The average yield 
to maturity rose to 5.89 percent, up from 5.86 percent late Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
