<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BBC World Television Cuts Staffing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The British Broadcasting Corp. is trimming staff  
and shaking up the schedule of its money-losing BBC World 
television news channel in hopes of winning more viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	BBC World, which is available in 200 countries but not inside  
Britain, was conceived as a profit-making venture. It reported a 
loss of $25 million last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The corporation announced Monday that it would cut 33  
journalists and 17 resource staffers, but said most would be 
shifted to other jobs in the BBC. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning in April, the channel will put a stronger emphasis on  
hourly newscasts and drop some of its political analysis 
programming. It will have a half-hour news bulletin every hour on 
weekdays and news bulletins and summaries on weekends. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our research shows viewers are using the channel to dip in for  
about 30 minutes to catch up on headlines and reports,'' said 
Rupert Gavin, chief executive of commercial division BBC Worldwide. 
``These changes will maximize viewership and also ensure that we 
are going to maximize advertising revenue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two hour-long analysis programs -- ``The World Today'' and  
``Europe Direct'' -- will be dropped in April, the BBC said. It will 
add a daily ``World Business'' program. 
</P>
<P>
	John Simpson, the BBC's world affairs editor, said there would  
be ``a huge public outcry'' over any cuts in the service. 
</P>
<P>
	``BBC World is the best international channel bar none, and that  
is not just my view,'' Simpson said. ``People as varied as the 
emperor of Japan, the president of France and Col. (Moammar) 
Ghadafi (of Libya) have said that to me, and told me they watch 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S.-based Cable News Network, BBC's rival for the  
international audience, announced in July that it was expanding its 
financial coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Cramer, president of CNN International, said Tuesday that  
the Atlanta-based cable network isn't particularly concerned about 
the BBC changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frankly, we're shrugging it off,'' Cramer said. ``BBC World is  
one of a number of competitors we have around the world.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
