<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on Cold Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices advanced in  
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade after an 
overnight freeze in Iowa raised concerns about harvesting. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean gains were minimal after little damage was reported from  
the freeze that sent temperatures plummeting as low as 24 degrees 
in northwestern Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The state of the soybean crop remains unclear after the U.S.  
Department of Agriculture reported Monday that 44 percent was in 
good to excellent condition -- extending a two-month decline in 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn prices also moved higher after a similar dip in the weekly  
conditions for that crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat inched higher on technical indications the market is  
oversold. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 3/4 cent to $2.73 a bushel;  
December corn rose 3/4 cents to $2.11 a bushel; December oats rose 1/2 
cent to $1.12 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans rose 2 1/2 cents to $4.89 1/2 
a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork bellies soared on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, where  
hog and cattle futures also were higher in early trading. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .28 cent to 66.85 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose .50 cent to 79.62 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose .65 cent to 45.30 cents a pound; February frozen 
pork bellies rose 3 cents to 56.77 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
