<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Backs Continued Russia Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is proposing new  
rules to fight money laundering, including requirements that 
storefront check cashers, brokerage firms and casinos notify 
authorities of suspicious activities the way banks do. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal surfaced in testimony Tuesday as the House Banking  
Committee began an inquiry into allegations of a huge 
money-laundering scheme involving the Russian mob and the Bank of 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has been charged, and U.S. investigators have not  
commented publicly on the case in which as much as $10 billion was 
alleged to have been funneled through the Bank of New York, the 
nation's 15th-largest bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, the leadoff witness for two  
days of hearings by the banking panel, defended the administration 
policy of continuing to provide aid to Russia. Republican leaders 
have denounced the policy in recent weeks as allegations of the 
money-laundering scheme grew. And some critics are blaming the 
episode on Vice President Al Gore, who maintains close ties with 
several Russian leaders and plays a major role in U.S.-Russian 
relations. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said the United States must keep supporting Russia or  
risk being branded as a scapegoat for Russia's failures. He told 
the lawmakers the Clinton administration, while demanding reform by 
the Russians, must keep in mind the importance of continued 
engagement because of that country's huge arsenal of nuclear 
weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``To quarantine, contain or write off Russia as too corrupt  
would ill serve our national interest,'' Summers testified. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that the International Monetary Fund, at U.S. urging,  
already has acted to ensure that billions of dollars in loans from 
the West are used for legitimate purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	The secretary also previewed the administration's proposal, to  
be formally released Thursday, for strengthening laws to make it 
more difficult for criminals to clean illicit earnings through 
banks and other financial institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of billions of dollars in drug-trafficking proceeds and  
other illegal gains are put into the nation's financial system each 
year. With the advent of tighter anti-money-laundering laws for 
banks, such as a requirement that they report to authorities cash 
transactions of $10,000 or more, many launderers have started using 
other channels such as money transmitters like Western Union and 
storefront businesses that cash checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus the administration's proposal to extend to money service  
businesses, brokerage firms and casinos the banks' requirement to 
file so-called suspicious activity reports. Summers said 
legislation also would be proposed to apply U.S. money-laundering 
laws to a wider range of international criminals, including corrupt 
foreign officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals are part of the administration's first national  
money-laundering strategy, which Congress directed the Treasury and 
Justice departments to submit early this year, before the Bank of 
New York case broke. The package seeks to bolster international 
cooperation in investigating money laundering and strengthen U.S. 
enforcement through tighter regulation of financial institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, the Banking Committee's chairman, said  
he also will introduce legislation to tighten laws and ``pierce the 
veil of secrecy that for too long has made it possible'' for 
offshore financial institutions to skirt U.S. laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money laundering may seem like a relatively modest crime, but  
it is a window into greater crimes'' that create the illegal funds, 
Leach said. He cited Russian government estimates that criminal 
groups control 40 percent of the country's economy and half its 
banking assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., was critical of the government's  
current policy. She challenged Summers to explain why no banks have 
been shut down for laundering money. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related development Tuesday, Switzerland's government  
announced that Swiss banks have frozen $16.8 million in accounts 
suspected to be linked to the Russian money-laundering case. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, World Bank President James Wolfensohn said the  
bank found no misuse of its funds in Russia in investigations of 
its 34 projects there. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
