<DOCNO> APW19990921.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 10:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Inflation Rises To 1.2 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The average annual inflation rate in  
the 11 countries that have adopted the euro as their common 
currency rose to 1.2 percent in August from 1.1 percent the 
previous month, the European Union's statistical office reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second consecutive monthly rise in average annual  
inflation for the ``euro zone'' which posted a rate of 0.9 percent 
in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the whole 15-nation European Union also rose to 1.2  
percent in August from 1.1 percent in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said rising oil prices, special taxes, summer sales and  
wage agreements were behind the slight increase. EU inflation 
remains largely stable. In August 1998, EU inflation was 1.3 
percent, and the average across the euro zone was 1.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest August rate was registered in the Netherlands with  
2.5 percent. Denmark and Ireland followed, both on 2.4 percent. 
Lowest rates were in France and Austria with 0.5 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Big Dairy Cos. Consolidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Suiza Foods Corp., the nation's leading milk  
processor, is acquiring Southern Foods Group, a company with such 
well-known regional dairy brands as Borden, Elsie and Meadow Gold. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company would be a national dairy powerhouse, with  
milk distribution in 46 states and combined annual sales of $6 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Southern takes us into geography that we weren't in, and but  
for Southern, we wouldn't be able to get into,'' said Suiza 
chairman Gregg Engles. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were one of the few big independent producers that we had  
an opportunity to do something with,'' he said. ``It really makes 
us a national dairy company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to dairy products, Suiza produces packaged food and  
ice. 
</P>
<P>
	``This clearly establishes Suiza as the leader of the fluid-milk  
market, with about a 20 percent market share,'' said analyst 
Romitha Mally of Goldman Sachs. She said the acquisition makes 
Suiza a national player and therefore more attractive to large 
supermarket chains that want to buy goods from suppliers with broad 
reach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a terrific deal. Suiza is breaking away from the  
pack,'' said John O'Neil of PaineWebber. He said Suiza now has a 
stable of strong regional milk labels and will try to increase 
sales of nationally known brands such as Borden. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza was founded in 1993 as a holding company for acquiring  
food and dairy processors and has grown rapidly through 
acquisitions, especially in the Southeast and Southern California, 
to 56 processing plants and 12,400 employees. It has made more than 
30 acquisitions in the past three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza's main rival, Dean Foods Co. of Franklin Park, Ill., with  
fiscal 1999 sales of nearly $3.8 billion, has also been acquiring 
smaller operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza and Southern, both based in Dallas, will form a joint  
venture to include all domestic milk processing activities of both 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza will own 66.2 percent of the venture, to be called the  
Suiza Fluid Dairy Group, with Southern's partner, Dairy Farmers of 
America Inc., owning the other 33.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	No cash will change hands in the deal, said Engles, but each  
company will contribute its assets to the joint venture. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Suiza had revenue of $3.3 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Southern, with revenue of nearly $1.2 billion in 1998, has 25  
plants and 5,100 employees. It is concentrated in Texas and 
Oklahoma but serves other markets, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Counting the full-year revenues of operations that Suiza has  
acquired during the past year, the revenue of the combined company 
for the 12 months ended June 30 would be about $6 billion, said 
Suiza's chief financial officer, Barry Fromberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza said the combination would generate $10 million in cost  
savings in the first year. But Engles said no layoffs of plant 
closings are expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Southern Foods chief executive, Pete Schenkel, will become  
president of domestic milk operations and board vice chairman of 
the new joint venture. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza also announced that its president and chief operating  
officer, G. Irwin Gordon, is leaving the company to pursue other, 
unspecified interests. His duties will be divided among several 
executives at different divisions, said Bill Brick, chief operating 
officer for U.S. fluid dairy operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza plans to obtain up to $2 billion of new financing to  
refinance the debt of both companies, for future acquisitions and 
other purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	Directors of both companies have unanimously approved the  
transaction, which faces a federal antitrust review. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Suiza rose 6 1/4  
cents to $33.31 1/4 a share. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Backs Continued Russia Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is proposing new  
rules to fight money laundering, including requirements that 
storefront check cashers, brokerage firms and casinos notify 
authorities of suspicious activities the way banks do. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal surfaced in testimony Tuesday as the House Banking  
Committee began an inquiry into allegations of a huge 
money-laundering scheme involving the Russian mob and the Bank of 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has been charged, and U.S. investigators have not  
commented publicly on the case in which as much as $10 billion was 
alleged to have been funneled through the Bank of New York, the 
nation's 15th-largest bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, the leadoff witness for two  
days of hearings by the banking panel, defended the administration 
policy of continuing to provide aid to Russia. Republican leaders 
have denounced the policy in recent weeks as allegations of the 
money-laundering scheme grew. And some critics are blaming the 
episode on Vice President Al Gore, who maintains close ties with 
several Russian leaders and plays a major role in U.S.-Russian 
relations. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said the United States must keep supporting Russia or  
risk being branded as a scapegoat for Russia's failures. He told 
the lawmakers the Clinton administration, while demanding reform by 
the Russians, must keep in mind the importance of continued 
engagement because of that country's huge arsenal of nuclear 
weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``To quarantine, contain or write off Russia as too corrupt  
would ill serve our national interest,'' Summers testified. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that the International Monetary Fund, at U.S. urging,  
already has acted to ensure that billions of dollars in loans from 
the West are used for legitimate purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	The secretary also previewed the administration's proposal, to  
be formally released Thursday, for strengthening laws to make it 
more difficult for criminals to clean illicit earnings through 
banks and other financial institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of billions of dollars in drug-trafficking proceeds and  
other illegal gains are put into the nation's financial system each 
year. With the advent of tighter anti-money-laundering laws for 
banks, such as a requirement that they report to authorities cash 
transactions of $10,000 or more, many launderers have started using 
other channels such as money transmitters like Western Union and 
storefront businesses that cash checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus the administration's proposal to extend to money service  
businesses, brokerage firms and casinos the banks' requirement to 
file so-called suspicious activity reports. Summers said 
legislation also would be proposed to apply U.S. money-laundering 
laws to a wider range of international criminals, including corrupt 
foreign officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals are part of the administration's first national  
money-laundering strategy, which Congress directed the Treasury and 
Justice departments to submit early this year, before the Bank of 
New York case broke. The package seeks to bolster international 
cooperation in investigating money laundering and strengthen U.S. 
enforcement through tighter regulation of financial institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, the Banking Committee's chairman, said  
he also will introduce legislation to tighten laws and ``pierce the 
veil of secrecy that for too long has made it possible'' for 
offshore financial institutions to skirt U.S. laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money laundering may seem like a relatively modest crime, but  
it is a window into greater crimes'' that create the illegal funds, 
Leach said. He cited Russian government estimates that criminal 
groups control 40 percent of the country's economy and half its 
banking assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., was critical of the government's  
current policy. She challenged Summers to explain why no banks have 
been shut down for laundering money. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related development Tuesday, Switzerland's government  
announced that Swiss banks have frozen $16.8 million in accounts 
suspected to be linked to the Russian money-laundering case. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, World Bank President James Wolfensohn said the  
bank found no misuse of its funds in Russia in investigations of 
its 34 projects there. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 12:20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Caddie Recalls 1927 Ryder Cup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass.(AP) -- Fred ``Jada'' Hill was a top golfer in  
Massachusetts for decades. But only now, at 89, is he enjoying his 
moment of wide celebrity. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill is one of the last connections to the first Ryder Cup -- the  
caddie for the great Gene Sarazen at Worcester Country Club in 
1927. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, he was back at the Ryder Cup. This time at The  
Country Club, just outside Boston, where the tournament begins 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was nothing like this back then,'' Hill said as about  
35,000 spectators watched the players practice -- 15 times as many 
people as had been at Worcester for the actual competition in '27. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ryder Cup began mainly to establish goodwill between  
American and British golfers. The Americans played hard when they 
had to, winning 9 1/2 to 2 1/2 in what was then a two-day competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill recalls Sarazen getting trounced by Charles Whitcombe in  
the singles match. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came back strong on the second nine. He was very  
competitive,'' Hill said. ``But when he heard the Americans had won 
most of the matches that day, he three-putted on purpose on the 
18th hole to give the British guy a half a point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite its gentlemanly roots, the tournament has grown into  
golf's most fiercely contested event. 
</P>
<P>
	At Worcester, the toughest competition might have been among the  
local caddies, with 200 of them trying to make some money off the 
Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill said he got a job because he was a top caddie. And it  
didn't hurt that he always bought some of the candy the caddie 
master sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill was paid $80 for carrying Sarazen's bags during a week of  
practice and play. The going rate for an 18-hole loop at the time 
was 75 cents, which is what Hill earned a couple of years earlier 
when he caddied for British professional Jim Barnes in the U.S. 
Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was a very large amount back then. Of course, Sarazen had  
been a caddie, so he treated us well,'' said Hill, noting that the 
captain of that first American Ryder Cup team, Walter Hagen, also 
had been a caddie. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American pros were just regular guys. They were fun to be  
around,'' Hill said. ``But the British people were different. They 
were very stiff, smoked pipes. It was funny, the difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicknamed ``Jada'' in grammar school because he was always  
singing a popular song that started with that word, Hill started 
caddying and playing golf at age 10. He won a city title, some club 
titles and four New England Public Linx titles. 
</P>
<P>
	He also held the course record of 64 at the Green Hill municipal  
course in Worcester. He thought about turning pro, but the money 
during the Depression was too uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a guy named Cyril Walker who was the U.S. Open  
winner (1924) and two years later he went back to caddying,'' Hill 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill went on to work in the packing room of the Norton Co.,  
which made grinding wheels. He made a name in golf by winning more 
than a few tournaments, but he never came close to the kind of life 
that would have enabled him to afford the Worcester Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
	At The Country Club, he was reminded of those days long ago at  
Worcester. 
</P>
<P>
	``The spectators were all wealthy people,'' Hill said. ``It was  
their game back then; they were the only ones who knew what was 
going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hill was accompanied to The Country Club by three men who had  
been spectators at Worcester -- Tom and Bill Kelleher and Al 
McIntyre. As they sat in a tent surrounded by a buffet and 12 
big-screen televisions, they marveled at the changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``At Worcester, I was 12 years old and I always remember that my  
brother bought me a ham sandwich and an orangeade. It was quite a 
treat. I think it cost about 49 cents,'' Tom Kelleher said. 
</P>
<P>
	A cheeseburger in the member-guest tent this week was $6.  
</P>
<P>
	In all, the PGA of America is expected to earn about $63 million  
from the 33rd Ryder Cup, with the fans spending millions on 
clothing and souvenirs. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, I don't have anything from that first Ryder Cup,'' Hill  
said. ``It didn't seem like that big of a deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now he does. He was given a cap this week by Worcester Country  
Club commemorating the inaugural competition. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hill remains a bit behind on the history he was a part of.  
Last year he sold eight gutta-percha golf balls in good shape to an 
antiques dealer for about $100. Those balls, replaced by 
rubber-core balls in the early 1900s, are worth from $200 to $1,000 
or more each, depending on condition, said Jere Pelletier, a 
collector who runs a Web page called The Golf Guy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I should have kept them, but so much time had gone  
by,'' said Hill, who quit playing golf two years ago under the 
stress of age and two artificial knee joints. ``I guess I still 
didn't think about making money off golf.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 08:11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Police Arrest Malaysian Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Three key opposition activists  
were arrested today in what appears to be a fresh crackdown on 
dissent following a wave of demonstrations in support of 
hospitalized opposition leader Anwar Ibrahim. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested leaders of the opposition National Justice  
Party, a party led by Anwar's wife, after they surrendered this 
morning at police headquarters in Kuala Lumpur. Four other 
activists were arrested Monday after a demonstration where 
protesters demanded Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's resignation 
</P>
<P>
	Officers dragged Tian Chua, the National Justice Party's vice  
president, and youth leader Mohamed Ezam Mohamed Nor inside the 
building. The two were accompanied by their lawyers, while 50 
supporters chanted slogans outside the police compound. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials from the National Justice Party said that Badrol Amin,  
another senior party member, was also picked up by the police 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government can arrest us but more leaders will rise up,''  
Tian said in a statement. ``The threats by Mahathir cannot oppress 
the people anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Assistant Commissioner Mat Zain Ibrahim warned, ``We will  
be making more arrests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of the four political parties that form the Alternative  
Front opposition coalition named Anwar -- who has been jailed on 
corruption charges -- as their candidate for prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	The coalition said in a statement that if it won elections  
widely expected by the end of the year, it would try to overturn 
his corruption conviction through a judicial inquiry into the 
``political conspiracy which has led to Anwar's imprisonment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An interim prime minister chosen by Parliament would lead  
Malaysia until Anwar was released from jail. 
</P>
<P>
	About 15,000 people gathered Monday night to mark the  
anniversary of the arrest of the former deputy prime minister. They 
demanded an independent investigation into claims that Anwar had 
been poisoned in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Anwar remained in the hospital today, where he has been for 12  
days, after his family and attorneys told a judge that medical 
tests showed dangerously high levels of arsenic in his urine. 
</P>
<P>
	The government hospital was still waiting for the results of  
tests conducted by independent laboratories, Anwar's lawyer 
Pawancheek Merican told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``We met him yesterday, and he looks pale,'' Panwancheek said.  
``When he sits down or lies down, his blood pressure goes up. And 
when he stands, his pressure drops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Anwar had been expected back in court for his sodomy trial  
Monday, but the judge said he had been told by doctors that he was 
unfit for court. 
</P>
<P>
	Anwar was fired a year ago by Mahathir, who claimed his deputy  
was corrupt and had committed sodomy, a crime in this predominantly 
Muslim nation. Anwar, who was convicted of abuse of power and 
sentenced to six years in prison, says all the charges against him 
were trumped up to end his challenge to Mahathir. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0025 </DOCNO>
