<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unilever NV To Narrow Brand List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Unilever NV, the Anglo-Dutch  
consumer products giant whose 1,600 brands include Lipton tea, 
Breyer's ice cream and other household names, plans to slash its 
product line to 400 in a bid to cut $1.4 billion in costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Unilever, the world's largest maker of household goods, said it  
would keep brands that are No. 1 or 2 in their respective markets. 
While the company wouldn't elaborate, analysts expected it to hold 
onto top U.S. and European brands and shed less popular ones in 
peripheral markets in Eastern Europe and parts of Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it would detail its plans by next spring and  
cut costs within three years as it improves efficiency and 
productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	In addtion to Lipton and Breyer's, Unilever brands include Flora  
margarine, Wisk laundry detergent, Calvin Klein perfume, Dove soap, 
Pepsodent and Close-Up toothpaste, Vaseline skin care products and 
the Bird's Eye and Gorton's frozen foods lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult to maintain focus when you have so many  
brands,'' said Darrell Duthrie, an analyst at MeesPierson in 
Amsterdam. He said Unilever almost certainly would discontinue the 
brands outside its new core group of 400 rather than sell them off 
``and give their competitors a step up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Unilever posted an 11 percent jump in net profit to  
$727 million last month for the second quarter of 1999, sales 
increased by only 3 percent over the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Unilever said it expects the narrowed focus to improve operating  
margins over the next 5 years in a push to become what co-chairmen 
Niall FitzGerald and Antony Burgmans called a ``leaner, fitter and 
faster'' company. 
</P>
<P>
	The company aims to increase sales of its largest brands by  
between 6 percent and 8 percent a year, or more, they said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 13:40:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Promises Aid to Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Even while offering sympathy and aid to Taiwan's  
earthquake victims, China subtly pressed its claim to the island 
Tuesday, appealing for unity and thanking other countries for their 
assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	Within hours of the quake, Chinese President Jiang Zemin said  
the disaster ``hurt the hearts of people on the mainland as the 
Chinese people on both sides of the Taiwan Strait are as closely 
linked as flesh and blood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are willing to offer any possible assistance to alleviate  
the quake-caused losses,'' Jiang said in remarks carried by the 
official Xinhua News Agency and read on state radio and television. 
</P>
<P>
	China's Red Cross announced it would provide the equivalent of  
$100,000 in disaster aid and more than $60,000 worth of relief 
supplies. Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said Beijing 
would provide ``all assistance within our capability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pledges of help contrasted with recent tensions between  
Beijing and the island it regards as a rebel province. Beijing has 
repeated threats to retake Taiwan by force and has held war games 
opposite the island since Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui 
suggested in July that the two sides were equal states. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan reacted cautiously to the Chinese overtures, expressing  
thanks while not outright accepting the assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	``This would be a good beginning to improving ties,'' Su Chi,  
chairman of Taiwan's top body on mainland relations, told 
reporters. ``I hope we can work on this basis and make efforts 
together to build up stable and peaceful relations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chances were slim, however, that both sides would use the deadly  
quake to better relations. China and Taiwan are heirs to opposing 
sides in a seven-decade civil war, and even simple matters take on 
political overtones. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhang, the Chinese Foreign Ministry spokeswoman, expressed  
thanks to other countries for offering help to Taiwan, subtly 
assuming the prerogative of the sovereign government. China has 
tried to isolate Taiwan diplomatically, insisting that its 
diplomatic partners sever formal ties with the island. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked by reporters if the quake could cause China to change  
its Taiwan policy, Zhang said Lee's comments and the earthquake 
were ``a completely different matter.'' Speaking at a routine 
briefing, she reiterated Beijing's condemnation of Lee's comments 
as ``a very dangerous step to split the country.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
