<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures were mixed Tuesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade, with no significant developments to 
give the market direction. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were pulled down by a drop in soybean oil prices after  
having risen early in the session on news of an overnight freeze in 
Iowa, South Dakota, Nebraska and Minnesota that raised concerns 
about the effect on harvesting. 
</P>
<P>
	Some crop loss was experienced but it was not thought to be  
major. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat prices dipped lower due to continued lack of export  
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn edged higher on technical buying.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 2 cents to $2.70 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose 1/2 cent to $2.10 3/4 a bushel; December oats rose 3/4 
cent to $1.12 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans fell 2 cents to $4.85 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork belly futures soared on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while hog and cattle futures also advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .18 cent to 66.75 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose .25 cent to 79.37 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose .17 cent to 44.82 cents a pound; February frozen 
pork bellies rose 3 cents to 56.77 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
