<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins Sign Special Teamer Mason </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- The Washington Redskins, looking to bolster  
their inconsistent special teams units, signed fifth-year 
linebacker Eddie Mason and released receiver Chris Thomas on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mason was signed late last year by Jacksonville and played in  
four regular season games and two playoff games, primarily on 
special teams. A sixth-round draft pick out of North Carolina by 
the New York Jets in 1995, Mason was named the Jets' special teams 
MVP as a rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas made the Redskins' roster in 1997 solely because of his  
standout play on special teams, but he was the culprit when the 
Dallas Cowboys pulled off a successful onside kick in the season 
opener. Instead of holding his spot, Thomas started retreating 
before the ball was kicked, allowing the Cowboys to recover the 
ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas was also part of a kickoff coverage unit that allowed two  
returns of 40-plus yards against the New York Giants on Sunday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
