<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 12:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> North Carolina Families in Shelters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TARBORO, N.C. (AP) -- After years of traveling from crop to crop,  
season after season, 16-year-old Maria Cerapio thought she had 
finally found a home. 
</P>
<P>
	She was thinking of going out for soccer at Martin Middle  
School. She even dreamed she might stay long enough to graduate 
here. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hurricane Floyd may force her family back on the road.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm trying to force my dad to stay here, even though all these  
things are going on,'' the girl with a waist-length ponytail said 
as she sat in the Tarboro High School parking lot in front of a row 
of portable toilets. ``But he said for our protection, he wants us 
to go back to Florida.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cerapios were among more than 2,000 eastern North Carolina  
residents taking shelter Tuesday in the high school from the waters 
of the swollen Tar River. Their trailer across the bridge in the 
predominantly black town of Princeville now sits under brown, oily 
water. 
</P>
<P>
	The family of migrant farm workers from Mexico arrived in  
Princeville in June, planning to continue a cycle that has taken 
them from the orange groves of Florida, the strawberry fields of 
California and the blueberry patches of Oregon. They often came to 
North Carolina so Venacio Cerapio, 38, could work the flue-cured 
tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	This time things promised to be different.  
</P>
<P>
	Cerapio and his wife, Aurelia, 34, found jobs making holiday  
dolls in a factory. The work was steady and not as backbreaking as 
the fields, and they liked the climate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just feel more comfortable here,'' he said as his daughter  
translated. ``It's not too hot or too cold.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The children had already started to establish themselves.  
</P>
<P>
	Umberto, 14, a skinny boy with a bright smile, was in seventh  
grade at Martin Middle and was playing forward for the basketball 
team, the Killer Bees. Maria, who was born in Oaxaca, Mexico, was 
catching up to her peers in school, working part of the time in 
eighth grade and part in ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like how they teach,'' she said. ``It is more challenging,  
and when they challenge you, you try harder. In Florida, it's easy, 
and when it's easy you don't really try hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But life here was not easy by any means.  
</P>
<P>
	The family's used single-wide trailer had just two bedrooms and  
one bathroom. Maria had to sleep in the living room with her 
brother and 10-year-old sister Janira so her parents and 
grandfather, Jacinto, 63, who also works at the doll factory, could 
have some privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Things got even more crowded recently when a family of five came  
to stay. But Maria liked the fact that four other branches of her 
family had settled in nearby Leggett. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, all of them are sharing cots on a basketball court.  
</P>
<P>
	Besides her clothes, the only things Maria got out of the  
trailer were her math and science books. She said she would need 
them to study for a test her teacher promised they would have when 
schools reopened. 
</P>
<P>
	``She will,'' Maria said, pulling a lollipop from her mouth to  
reveal two rows of perfect teeth. ``I know this teacher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The family had a chance to move to a shelter with hot showers  
and private rooms in Wilson, but they were afraid to leave Tarboro 
for fear of missing out on aid information for their area. While 
the grown-ups sat on cots and looked at 2-day-old newspapers, the 
children played tag in the parking lots -- when it wasn't raining. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelter life was already taking its toll. Maria's cousin,  
Beatrice Rojas, 11, buried her head in a cot and sobbed 
uncontrollably Tuesday after a fight with Umberto. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's depressed because she lost everything,'' Maria said as  
she comforted the girl. 
</P>
<P>
	Umberto cursed the storm. ``It's spoiled everything,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Officials said it could be a week before the Cerapios and others  
are allowed back into Princeville to look at their homes. With 
barely a half-hour to flee, the family left with little else but 
their Bible and the clothes they were wearing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The things we lost, we could get back, but our lives are more  
important,'' the father said as he leaned against his gray van with 
nearly 100,000 miles on it. ``I don't really feel that bad, because 
God wants it like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maria, too, knows that the trailer is gone. She just doesn't  
want to admit it. ``I really got attached to it here,'' she said, 
her smile fading in the darkened shelter hallway. ``This was going 
to be our home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITORS NOTE: Allen G. Breed is the AP's Southeast regional  
writer, based in Raleigh. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
