<DOCNO> APW19990921.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Temporary Homes Coming to N.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TARBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Emergency officials began erecting villages  
of trailer homes and campers Tuesday for 1,000 families whose homes 
were still under the floodwaters of Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	The temporary homes could open within a few days.  
</P>
<P>
	Many weary evacuees welcomed the chance to get out of shelters.  
</P>
<P>
	``It'll be a home. I can call that a home because there's nobody  
but me and my family in one camper,'' said Angela Davis, who has 
been staying with her son, daughter and hundreds of others at 
Tarboro High School. 
</P>
<P>
	The campers and mobile home villages are being set up outside  
Rocky Mount and Greenville and will have electricity, running water 
and air conditioning. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Floyd dumped 20 inches of rain on eastern North  
Carolina last Thursday with catastrophic effect: 39 confirmed 
deaths, 30,000 flooded homes, 10,000 people in shelters. About 
47,000 people remained without power, and nearly 300 roads remained 
closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Altogther, the storm was responsible for more than 60 deaths  
from the Bahamas to New England. In New Jersey, more than a million 
still did not have safe water to drink. 
</P>
<P>
	At Tarboro High, home to an estimated 1,500 to 2,000 evacuees,  
people were sleeping on cots in classrooms and in the gymnasium. 
The school had no running water. People bathed in shower tents 
hooked up to water tankers. Portable toilets were overflowing. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have right now is like a small city,'' said Dave Stone  
of the American Red Cross, the shelter's manager. ``It would be 
nice to have flushable toilets, but that's not in the foreseeable 
future. Thank God we've got power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State officials continued to assess the agricultural damage. At  
least 2.9 million poultry and 100,000 hogs drowned. Sewage plants 
and hog waste lagoons were swamped by the fast, brown waters. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffins, bloated animal carcasses and household goods could be  
seen bobbing in the polluted floodwaters across an 
18,000-square-mile area. 
</P>
<P>
	More rain fell Tuesday, delaying efforts to fire up incinerators  
to begin destroying the carcasses of hundreds of thousands of 
drowned hogs, chickens and turkeys to prevent the spread of 
disease. About an inch fell in the flooded areas, with forecasters 
warning of thunderstorms later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The early damage estimate of $1.3 billion is expected to soar  
and may well exceed the $6 billion for Hurricane Fran in 1996, the 
state's costliest natural disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Pilots delivering food and bottled water to shelters continued  
to look for stranded people from the air. The state has said about 
1,500 people are still believed stranded. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
