<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Broadly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell broadly against other currencies  
Tuesday, weighed down by a surprise move by the Bank of Japan, a 
huge U.S. trade deficit in July and improved business sentiment in 
Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell against the yen in early trading after the Bank  
of Japan, defying pressure from Japanese politicians, refused to 
alter its money supply policy as a way of influencing exchange 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors had expected Japan's central bank to make some policy  
gesture as a way to pull back the yen, which has soared against the 
dollar this summer. When the bank stood its ground, the dollar 
plunged even further against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	By late afternoon in New York, the dollar was quoted at 104.87  
yen, down sharply from 106.38 yen late Monday. The dollar was 
quoted at 105.42 yen in late Tokyo trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar took another blow when the Commerce Department  
reported a record trade deficit of $25.2 billion in July, 
reflecting a continued trend of Americans buying more goods from 
overseas than they sell. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. trade imbalance results in foreign companies holding  
more and more dollars in their accounts. That trend weakens the 
dollar as investors fear that those companies may be tempted to 
redeem their dollars for their own currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the euro gained against the dollar following a  
report showing that German business sentiment improved in August at 
a rate that was faster than economists had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0485, up from $1.0383 late Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5287 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5476, and 1.4750 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4775. The British 
pound rose to $1.6311 from $1.6207. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8653 German 
marks, down from 1.8835; 6.2558 French francs, down from 6.3170; 
and 1,846.53 Italian lire, down from 1,864.67. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
