<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Sept. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan Quake Kills More Than 1,700  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Rescuers scrambled through the night  
Tuesday to unearth thousands of people trapped under debris from 
Taiwan's second-deadliest earthquake, which killed at least 1,712 
people and injured over 4,000. Almost 3,000 people were believed to 
remain underneath rubble. More than 100,000 Taiwanese were 
homeless. The 7.6-magnitude quake toppled houses and high-rise 
apartment complexes across central Taiwan. Roads buckled, chunks of 
land rose up to create new hills and a bridge was left dangling in 
the air. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Sink; Dow Ends Down 225.43  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today, pulled lower by  
increasing concerns about the weakening dollar, the growing U.S. 
trade deficit and upcoming earnings reports. The Dow Jones 
industrial average ended down 225.43 points at 10,598.47 after 
falling as much as 272.03 during the session. The Dow's decline, 
which amounted to 2 percent, was its biggest point drop since it 
fell 235.53 on May 27. On the NYSE, declining issues outnumbered 
advancers 2,362-492. The Nasdaq fell 65 to 2,821.15. 

</P>
<P>
	Tropical Storm Harvey Approaches Fla.  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Tropical Storm Harvey changed course and bore down  
on South Florida today with 50 mile-an-hour winds and heavy rain, 
closing schools and prompting an emergency declaration from the 
governor. More than 10 inches of rain has caused some street 
flooding. Harvey is centered about 30 miles south of Naples, and is 
moving to the east-southeast at 12 miles per hour. Out in the 
Atlantic, a hurricane warning is in effect for Bermuda as Gert 
moved to within 135 miles of the island today with top wind of 110 
miles per hour. It is moving toward the north at about 13 miles per 
hour. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Says U.N. Must Do More  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- President Clinton challenged the United  
Nations and countries in Africa, Asia and elsewhere today to 
strengthen their ability to stop mass killings like those in Kosovo 
and East Timor. Clinton suggested the United Nations play an 
expanded role in preventing mass slaughter and dislocation. Among 
other things, Clinton said international forces were needed with 
the training to fill the gap between local police and military 
peacekeepers. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: No Politics in Clemency  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton told Congress he granted  
clemency to 14 Puerto Rican nationalists on the belief ``that a 
punishment should fit the crime.'' No politics was involved, he 
said. Clinton outlined his position in a five-page letter to Rep. 
Henry Waxman of California, who read it at the start of a House 
Government Reform Committee hearing on the clemency. Waxman is the 
senior Democrat on the committee. Clinton said he based his 
decision on the ``extremely lengthy sentences'' the prisoners were 
serving, most between 35 and 90 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Gov't Ends Arguments Vs. Microsoft  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government wrapped up its historic  
antitrust trial today against Microsoft Corp., its lawyers accusing 
the company in closing arguments of acting as a vigilant monopolist 
intent on squelching upstart rivals at the expense of consumers. 
Citing dozens of internal e-mails and sworn testimony, government 
lawyers portrayed Microsoft as ruthless in its efforts to protect 
the dominance of its lucrative Windows software. Microsoft, which 
was also to make its closing arguments today, said the government 
``truly has blinders on when it looks at what is going on in the 
high-tech industry.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Minorities Fuel Population Growth  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Census Bureau study showing that minorities  
will fuel almost all of America's population growth in the next 50 
years presents great economic opportunities for minority 
businesses, Commerce Secretary William M. Daley said today. In 50 
years, America's population growth will come almost entirely from 
minority groups, according to the study. America's population will 
grow by 50 percent, from 268.2 million people to 393.9 million, it 
estimates. Almost 90 percent of the growth will come from 
minorities, a group that includes Asians, American Indians, blacks 
and people of Hispanic descent, the study says. 

</P>
<P>
	Falcons' Anderson Out for Season  
</P>
<P>
	SUWANEE, Ga. (AP) -- Atlanta Falcons All-Pro running back Jamal  
Anderson is out for the season after tearing a ligament in his 
right knee in last night's 24-7 loss to Dallas. On his third carry, 
Anderson took a handoff, attempted to cut to the left and went down 
in obvious pain without being touched. ``It happens and you hate 
it, but you can't dwell on it,'' Atlanta coach Dan Reeves said 
about losing Anderson's. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PAULINE MILLARD  



  	   	
</P>
