<DOCNO> APW19990921.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Prices Up After Brit. Auction  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gold futures took their biggest one-day leap in more than a year  
Tuesday, rising $6 an ounce after a British auction brought a more 
glittering price for the metal than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, prices of natural gas futures fell and frozen  
pork bellies advanced sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold, once the commodity of choice, lost its luster years ago  
and remains at less than a third of its all-time high of $875 per 
troy ounce in 1980. Back then, Soviet troops were moving into 
Afghanistan, the United States had double-digit inflation and oil 
prices were soaring. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, however, central banks have been dumping their  
gold reserves in favor of better-performing investments such as 
U.S. Treasury bonds. Prices dipped to a 20-year low of $255 an 
ounce this summer and have remained stagnant. 
</P>
<P>
	The British Treasury joined the get-out-of-gold rush this year  
and went ahead with its second sale on Tuesday despite continuing 
criticism that selling when the price has plummeted so far amounts 
to a government giveaway. 
</P>
<P>
	A falling U.S. dollar helped bring slightly above-market prices,  
with the Bank of England sale fetching $255.75 an ounce for its 25 
metric tons. 
</P>
<P>
	That's still nearly $27 less than what the metal was selling for  
when the government announced the sale in May. But experts were 
encouraged by the strong interest by South Africa's Gold Fields, 
the world's No. 2 gold producer, which bought 12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The overall tone is far superior to the last auction and  
better than the market anticipated,'' said Bill O'Neill, senior 
futures strategist for Merrill Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold finished at $261.80 an ounce on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	A gold trader for Fimat USA Inc. in New York said expectations  
are that the price will now settle in somewhere between $255 and 
$275. But ``all bets are off depending on what the stock market is 
doing,'' said the trader, who declined to give his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Unseasonably cool temperatures sent natural gas futures  
spiraling lower for the seventh time in the last eight trading days 
on the New York Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The autumn chill has brought a sudden halt to demand for gas to  
generate electricity for air conditioning, and the high-demand 
season for heating gas remains weeks away. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas for delivery in October fell 9.2 cents to $2.427 per  
million British thermal units. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil, meanwhile, rose again on the eve of the meeting of  
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries in Vienna, 
Austria. OPEC is widely expected to extend current production 
levels, which would keep supplies tight. 
</P>
<P>
	October crude rose 17 cents to $24.46 a barrel; October heating  
oil fell .47 cent to 59.78 cents a gallon; October unleaded regular 
gasoline fell .32 cent to 68.13 cents a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude for November delivery rose 2  
cents to $22.68 on the International Petroleum Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, pork belly futures advanced  
more than 5 percent, a day after a report showed much less in cold 
storage -- 435.9 million pounds -- than had been estimated. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Roose, an analyst for U.S. Commodities Inc. in West Des  
Moines, Iowa, said the reaction to the report turned into a 
stampede. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still a record cold storage number, and still much larger  
than last year,'' he said. ``It's just not as big as last year. The 
market probably overreacted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	February frozen pork bellies rose 3 cents to 56.77 cents a  
pound. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
