<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Officials: Russia To Make Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia will make all its October debt payments,  
both foreign and domestic, even if the newest installment of an 
International Monetary Fund loan is delayed, Russian finance 
officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF approved a $4.5 billion loan to Russia in late July and  
released $640 million of it shortly thereafter. The Russian 
government is waiting for the next $640 million, but the IMF has 
said that portion will be delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	First Deputy Finance Minister Alexei Kudrin said Tuesday that  
even if the credit comes late, Russia will meet its obligations 
next month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have enough hard currency resources to pay the debt,''  
Kudrin was quoted as saying by the ITAR-Tass news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF is considering whether it should impose additional  
controls on the use of IMF funds in Russia. It is also 
investigating allegations of financial corruption involving the 
Russian government. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, Finance Minister Mikhail Kasyanov told reporters  
that Russia is prepared to negotiate for a substantial reduction in 
its foreign debt to the London Club of commercial creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not specify how much of a break Russia requested. The two  
sides talked last week and will take up the discussion again when 
the next round of London Club talks resumes in Frankfurt on 
Thursday, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia owes the commercial creditors of its Soviet-era debt  
around $30 billion. It has missed $1.3 billion in payments since 
December. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is looking for an agreement that will let it  
reduce its debt burden enough to cover domestic spending needs 
while still servicing its foreign and domestic debt, Kasyanov said. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that Russia's current debt burden would require it to  
use up to 70 percent of its budget revenues to finance debt service 
payments. The 2000 draft budget earmarks 27 percent of revenues for 
debt payments, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
