<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aussies Plan Pre-Olympic Drug Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Out-of-competition drug tests on  
athletes preparing for next year's Olympics will be held outside 
Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC coordination commission head Jacques Rogge said Tuesday that  
in addition to some 2,000 tests at various sports events there will 
be another 200 to 400 out-of-competition tests. 
</P>
<P>
	``They would be conducted on accredited athletes who enter  
Australian territory,'' Rogge said during a visit to check on 
Sydney organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Sydney Organizing Committee for the Olympic  
Games completed the sale of its plans on how to prepare for an 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee has agreed to pay SOCOG $3.5  
million for the rights to those plans, which will be passed on to 
future host cities such as Athens, Greece; Salt Lake City; and 
Turin, Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will definitely allow them in many fields to win a year or  
two because you don't have to reinvent the wheel,'' Rogge said. 
</P>
<P>
	The information covers a range of subjects -- from organizational  
structure to the amount of milk athletes drink to the number of 
buses needed for an Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games showed  
SOCOG a lot of goodwill, one thing we have learned to our cost in 
undertaking this enormous task is the lack of useful management 
knowledge passed on from one city to the next,'' IOC chief 
executive Sandy Hollway said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge's group was making its ninth visit to Sydney, with another  
two trips scheduled before the games begin. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he is convinced SOCOG has fixed problems with its  
results system. All technology must be tested 75 days before the 
opening ceremony Sept. 15. That is expected to prevent many 
problems that blighted the Atlanta Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The results system faces a major test Sunday in which SOCOG will  
simulate results from 21 sites. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
