<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goldman Sachs Profits Beat Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Driven by a strong overseas presence, Goldman  
Sachs Group Inc. beat Wall Street's predictions with profits that 
soared 94 percent in its third fiscal quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The investment bank on Tuesday posted net income of $638  
million, or $1.31 a share, for the quarter ended Aug. 27, easily 
beating analysts' estimates of $1.09. Goldman earned pro forma 
profits of $329 million, or 69 cents a share in the third quarter 
last year, when the company was still privately held. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest three-month period marked Goldman's first full  
quarter as a publicly-held company. 
</P>
<P>
	Total third-quarter revenues were $6.44 billion, up from $5.74  
billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``All in all, we're pretty impressed with the quarter,'' said  
Lauren Smith, an investment banking analyst with Putnam, Lovell &AMP; 
Thornton. She cited Goldman's active role in international mergers 
and acquisitions, and stock and bond underwriting for the company's 
strong third quarter results. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Goldman Sachs fell $1.62 1/2 to $59.12 1/2 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldman chief financial officer David Viniar said in a  
conference call with reporters that Goldman was involved in seven 
of the 10 largest international mergers and acquistions during the 
bank's fiscal third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldman also benefited from investors' continued interest in  
initial public stock offerings from technology firms, especially 
anything Internet-related. The company reported $1.2 billion in 
third-quarter revenues from its investment banking arm, a 25 
percent increase from a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Goldman's successful third-quarter IPOs was Red Hat Inc.,  
a vendor for the popular Linux software line. Red Hat's stock has 
risen almost 700 percent to over $110 a share from $14 since its 
IPO last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very strong quarter across the board in investment  
banking,'' Viniar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Viniar added that Goldman was ``cautiously optimistic'' for the  
bank's fourth-quarter results, when charges related to Goldman's 
$531 million purchase of the Hull Group are expected to be factored 
into the company's earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldman's purchase of Chicago-based Hull Group is another effort  
by Goldman to move into electronic trading. Hull Group matches buy 
and sell orders on several electronic trading networks. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of 1999, Goldman posted earnings of  
$1.8 billion, or $3.73 a share, compared with $1.3 billion or $2.64 
a share during the same period a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine-month revenues climbed to $18.7 billion from $18.2 billion.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
