<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Restoration of F-22 Funds Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans are moving toward reviving one of  
the Air Force's top priorities, its new F-22 stealth fighter, as 
GOP congressional leaders seek to clear obstacles to must-pass 
spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	House-Senate bargainers will try to decide how much money for  
the F-22 they will provide in hopes of completing a compromise $267 
billion defense bill for the coming fiscal year that lawmakers 
could vote on soon. Fiscal 2000 begins on Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking on condition of anonymity, congressional aides said  
Monday that Republican leaders have ordered negotiators from the 
House and Senate to restore at least some of the $1.8 billion for 
the F-22 that the House killed in July. 
</P>
<P>
	That money is enough to buy the first six of the warplanes,  
which the Air Force envisions as the chief guarantor of U.S. air 
supremacy in coming years. The F-22 is supported by the Senate and 
the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	According to aides, House bargainers offered over the weekend to  
provide enough money for two of the aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,  
discussed the dispute Monday with Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., 
chairman of the House Appropriations Committee subcommittee that 
oversees the Pentagon's budget. Stevens told a reporter that he had 
offered ``some savings'' from the F-22 program but said it was 
``rejected out of hand'' by Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla., was  
quoted by the St. Petersburg Times on Sunday as saying GOP leaders 
agreed to purchase an unspecified number of F-22s next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Restoration of the money would mark a major victory for the Air  
Force and Lockheed Martin Corp., the aircraft's prime contractor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force already has spent $25 billion to develop the F-22  
and plans to spend an additional $40 billion to build 339 of them. 
That would be a price tag of nearly $200 million per plane, the 
most expensive jet fighter ever built. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides its ability to evade radar, the F-22 would carry  
computers letting pilots destroy targets well before they are 
visible and would be able to cruise at supersonic speeds without 
using afterburners. The Air Force hopes the first F-22s will be 
part of its fleet of warplanes in 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics, led by Lewis, say the aircraft is too expensive and  
would divert funds from other Air Force priorities, such as 
designing a new bomber. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis spokesman Jim Specht declined to comment on the  
bargaining, saying only that the lawmaker considers the F-22 
question ``an unsettled situation at this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the House bill, the $1.8 billion sought for the F-22 was  
used for other programs, including buying more F-15 and F-16 
fighters and KC-130J air tanker planes not requested by President 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, Congress has completed just four of the 13 spending  
bills for the coming year. Already, six face potential vetoes over 
such disagreements as a proposal to eliminate the AmeriCorps 
national service program to language forbidding the District of 
Columbia from distributing free hypodermic needles to drug abusers. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent days, Republicans have been moving toward Clinton  
administration and Democratic positions on several fronts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate has reduced or eliminated cuts the House has made in  
NASA and housing. And the two chambers' leaders have agreed to 
provide $7.6 billion in emergency aid for farmers because of low 
commodity prices, something congressional Democrats had been 
demanding. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
