<DOCNO> APW19990921.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 08:18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Won't Ease Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Bank of Japan refused today to ease monetary  
policy to curb a rapid rise in the value of the yen against the 
dollar, surprising the financial markets which had expected a 
relaxation. 
</P>
<P>
	In a move that sent the yen soaring, the BOJ said that monetary  
policy should not be used to control the exchange rate, and the 
bank cannot act just because markets expect a move. 
</P>
<P>
	Government leaders, who have warned that gains by the yen could  
derail Japan's nascent economic recovery, were not happy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The BOJ is not doing something that is obviously needed, and  
is becoming obstinate.'' said Ichizo Ohara, a member of the lower 
house of parliament and policy adviser to Prime Minister Keizo 
Obuchi. 
</P>
<P>
	``The BOJ executives are thinking only about themselves,'' he  
added, referring to speculation that the BOJ defied the Finance 
Ministry's push to further ease monetary policy in order to assert 
its independence. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen is considered damaging to Japanese companies  
because it makes their exports more expensive abroad, and thus less 
competitive, while reducing the value of foreign profits in yen 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had said that a decision to ease monetary policy could  
curb upward pressure on the yen if it helped lower long-term 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists saw the situation differently than politicians.  
</P>
<P>
	Before the BOJ announcement, Japan's chief economic planner said  
the currency's upward trend is not necessarily bad news for the 
fragile economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``While the appreciation of the yen hurts the export sector, it  
also helps to considerably reduce the cost of imports for other 
firms,'' said Taichi Sakaiya, head of the Economic Planning Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Within minutes of the BOJ announcement, the dollar plunged more  
than 2 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 105.42 yen by late afternoon, down 2.50 yen  
from late Monday in Tokyo and below its late New York level of 
106.38 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In a rare move, the BOJ issued a statement explaining its  
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``The effect of such steps, even if there is one, is one-time  
only and wouldn't be long-lasting, so as a central bank, we can't 
take policy steps for which we can't explain the purpose or the 
effect,'' the BOJ said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the announcement, BOJ governor Masaru Hayami said that the  
bank will continue using intervention to smooth currency market 
movements. 
</P>
<P>
	Many government officials have argued that the government should  
intervene to stabilize the foreign exchange market, and that it 
should coordinate with the United States to that end. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation has been widespread in the media that Japan has  
already requested U.S. aid in combating the yen's appreciation 
against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said today that he and  
U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers will probably discuss 
exchange rates when they meet later this week in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, economists said Japan need not worry so much about a  
strong yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Naldrett, an economist at Dresdner Kleinwort Benson in  
Tokyo, said a strong yen wouldn't hurt the economy since forces are 
already in place for recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are comparing this appreciation to the '90s, when it  
killed the economy,'' Naldrett said. At that time, monetary policy 
was tight and interest rates were high, smothering domestic demand. 
``The two episodes are entirely different.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
