<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Tycoon May Want LA NFL Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Marvin Davis, who has shown interest in  
building a stadium and bringing an NFL team to Hollywood Park in 
Inglewood, reportedly is considering whether to pay more than $1 
billion for a team and facility. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times reported today that Davis met with NFL  
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue in San Francisco on Monday night. The 
league is trying to decide where to place a new expansion 
franchise, which would be its 32nd team. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL's deadline for dealing exclusively with groups in Los  
Angeles passed last Wednesday, but the league was continuing to 
speak with representatives here beyond that self-imposed deadline. 
However, Houston -- which has a stadium proposal and financing plan 
set to go -- is considered the likely favorite to get the new team. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, 74, and his sons, Gregg and John, met last week with  
retired Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway, the newspaper said. 
There had been preliminary talks with Elway's representatives about 
the possibility of giving Elway a 10 percent stake in the team in 
exchange for becoming team president, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Finnigan, a Davis representative at Hollywood Park, did  
not immediately return a phone call from The Associated Press 
placed before business hours today. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, an oil tycoon, faces a decision later this week. The  
option he holds on approximately 100 acres of land at Hollywood 
Park expires Friday unless he puts down a $250,000 payment. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL's expansion committee plans to discuss possibilities for  
the new franchise at its Oct. 5 meeting in Atlanta. The league's 
full membership begins meetings on Oct. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said Monday that the league is  
continuing to talk with Los Angeles representatives. One group 
backing the Los Angeles Coliseum has maintained contact with the 
league. Tagliabue met with Coliseum partners Eli Broad and Ed Roski 
over the weekend, the paper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis told the league that he has the money to bring a team to  
Los Angeles and would not ask the league to contribute $150 million 
toward the construction of the stadium, the Times said. He also 
said his sons would take ownership of the new team. 
</P>
<P>
	He has expressed interest in professional teams before, among  
them the Broncos, the Dallas Cowboys and the Oakland A's. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times said Davis has refused to publicly comment on his  
reported interest in securing a team for Los Angeles. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
