<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Probes Newborn Hospital Stays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A study in Ohio found that ``drive-through  
deliveries'' did not increase the likelihood that infants would 
have to be hospitalized again, as some doctors had feared. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, the researchers and an expert not involved with the  
study said the results should not be interpreted to mean that 
newborns and their mothers are well-served by hospital stays of 
less than 48 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the babies' rates of rehospitalization actually  
declined during the four-year study period, their rate of 
outpatient treatment increased 117 percent, and they were also 
slightly more likely to have a home care visit or go to the 
emergency room. 
</P>
<P>
	``This study, I think, could be sorely misused by managed care  
to indicate that early discharge is in fact safe, and that's not 
what this study says,'' said Dr. James A. Lemons, chairman of the 
Committee on Fetus and Newborn of the American Academy of 
Pediatrics. 
</P>
<P>
	If babies are discharged too early, doctors may fail to detect  
heart and lung problems, intestinal obstructions and other major 
complications that can be fatal, Lemons said Tuesday from 
Indianapolis, where he heads neonatology at Indiana University 
Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Other studies have supported that belief. A 1997 study of  
310,000 births in Washington state found that healthy newborns who 
remained hospitalized for more than a day generally fared better 
than those who went home a few hours after birth. 
</P>
<P>
	The new study, published in Wednesday's Journal of the American  
Medical Association, covered 1991 to 1995, before a federal law 
began mandating that insurance companies cover at least 48 hours of 
hospitalization for newborns and their mothers. 
</P>
<P>
	The authors, led by Dr. Uma R. Kotagal of Children's Hospital  
Medical Center in Cincinnati, reviewed the records of more than 
102,000 healthy, full-term newborns of Ohio mothers receiving 
Medicaid. Their average length of stay decreased from 2.2 days in 
1991 to 1.6 days in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The share of newborns who were sent home less than a day after a  
vaginal delivery or two days after a Caesarean birth increased from 
21 percent to 59.8 percent during that time. 
</P>
<P>
	But the rates of rehospitalization within two weeks of discharge  
went down 23 percent, the researchers said. They speculated that a 
campaign by some Ohio hospitals to better coordinate care for 
newborns after discharge may have been part of the reason. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
