<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea Wants Lift on All Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North Korea welcomed the partial  
lifting of U.S. economic sanctions and asked Tuesday for the 
remaining sanctions to be removed as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a good development, though it is not comprehensive and  
came belatedly,'' said the Korean Central News Agency, North 
Korea's official overseas news outlet. ``The United States should 
show good faith by lifting the remaining sanctions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The response came four days after Washington partially lifted a  
half-century of restrictions against the North as part of a new 
policy of engaging the impoverished communist country. 
</P>
<P>
	Restrictions were eased on U.S. imports of raw materials and  
most goods made in North Korea, sales of most U.S. consumer goods 
and financial services to the North and U.S. investment in the 
North's agriculture and transportation system, among other things. 
</P>
<P>
	But sanctions remain against sales of U.S. weapons and  
missile-related technology, unlicensed exports of ``dual-use'' 
goods or technology -- items that could have military uses -- 
regulated by the Commerce Department, and unauthorized financial 
transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was the most significant gesture toward the North since  
the 1950-53 Korean War, including a modest trade opening in 1995. 
The sanctions have been in place since 1953. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States acted a week after talks with North Korea in  
Berlin, where the North agreed not to test-fire a long-range 
missile as long as dialogue continues. 
</P>
<P>
	The North's rival, South Korea, also welcomed the development  
while Japan said it might follow suit if North Korea proves it is 
serious about halting missile tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Former U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry will discuss North  
Korea policy with South Korean leaders this week, officials here 
said Tuesday. Perry, President Clinton's policy coordinator on 
North Korea, will arrive Wednesday in Seoul and meet with President 
Kim Dae-jung, Foreign Affairs and Trade Minister Hong Soon-young 
and Unification Minister Lim Dong-won. 
</P>
<P>
	The North repeated demands Tuesday that have been rejected by  
the United States and South Korea, including the complete 
withdrawal of U.S. forces from South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States fought on South Korea's side during the Korean  
War, and about 37,000 U.S. troops remain in the South under a 
defense treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	With its economy in tatters, North Korea has been relying on  
outside aid to feed its 22 million people since 1995. Its farm 
industry has been ruined by decades of mismanagement aggravated by 
years of bad weather. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0074 </DOCNO>
