<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Twins 4, Athletics 0  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Jason Ryan took a shutout into the  
seventh inning to earn his first major league victory and the 
Oakland Athletics' playoff hopes faded some more Monday night with 
a 4-0 loss to the Minnesota Twins. 
</P>
<P>
	Before just 6,512, Oakland's second-smallest home crowd this  
season, the A's dropped five games behind idle Boston in the AL 
wild-card race. Oakland has 13 games remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Appier (15-13) allowed three runs and eight hits in 6 2-3  
innings, dropping to 6-4 since the A's acquired him from Kansas 
City on July 31. He struck out a season-high eight but matched his 
career high for losses in a season. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan (1-2), a 23-year-old right-hander making his seventh career  
start, allowed five hits in six-plus innings, struck out one and 
walked three. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Coomer drove in three runs for the Twins, who have won  
consecutive games for the first time since Sept. 5-6 against Tampa 
Bay. Minnesota is 5-14 in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan allowed just one runner past second base. John Jaha doubled  
leading off the second and was thrown out at the plate by Matt 
Lawton when he tried to score on Ben Grieve's single to right. 
</P>
<P>
	After Ryan walked Jason Giambi starting the seventh, Kevin  
Miller got Matt Stairs to ground into a double play. Rich Becker 
hit a drive to the warning track in center with two on and two 
outs, but Torii Hunter ran it down with a fine over-the-shoulder 
catch. 
</P>
<P>
	Coomer's sacrifice fly drove in Brent Gates in the first, and he  
hit RBI singles in the seventh and ninth innings. Hunter singled 
home a run in the sixth. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* The A's smallest home crowd was 5,377 against Anaheim on  
April 13. ... Ryan has never started a day game and had not started 
a game on grass until Monday night. ... The Twins have won 19 of 
the last 24 games in which they score first. ... Grieve has not 
driven in a run in 26 at-bats against Minnesota this season despite 
a .370 career batting average against the Twins, his best against 
any team. ... Stairs needs one homer for career No. 100. ... 
Giambi's .381 batting average since the All-Star break is the best 
in the American League and his 64 RBIs tie Texas' Rafael Palmiero 
for the lead. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
