<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 08:00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reagan Bio Mixes Fiction, History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- David McCullough, Pulitzer Prize winner for his  
book on Harry Truman, was intrigued that a fellow writer had 
imagined himself a lifelong acquaintance of Ronald Reagan in his 
biography of the former president. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's such a beautiful afternoon here on Martha's Vineyard that  
I thought I'd go help John Adams mow hay,'' McCullough, author of 
``Truman'' and a Massachusetts resident, said with a laugh Monday. 
``I've been working on a book about Adams for five or six years and 
the prospect of spending some time with him is quite appealing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Dutch,'' an authorized biography, Edmund Morris uses a  
technique more in the spirit of ``Forrest Gump'' than historical 
scholarship. Morris, himself a Pulitzer winner for his biography of 
Theodore Roosevelt, invents a narrator for his current book. And 
not just any narrator, but ``Edmund Morris,'' a contemporary of 
Reagan's. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dutch'' was commissioned back in the mid-1980s, when Reagan  
was president, and Morris was given extensive access. Although the 
author was born nearly 30 years after his subject, he places 
himself with Reagan on the football field, the college campus and 
at the Army Air Force's motion picture unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Few have seen advanced copies of ``Dutch,'' which will go on  
sale next week, but it has already been criticized by historians 
and Reagan associates. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as he levels with the reader, I don't think it's a  
problem,'' McCullough said. ``I have great respect for Edmund 
Morris. He's a first-rate biographer and a first-rate author. He's 
chosen to try something unusual, but the author is free to do what 
an author wishes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris' approach is highly unusual for biography, but it's  
common for fiction. In Gore Vidal's ``Creation,'' set during the 
fifth century B.C., the author invents a traveling diplomat who 
meets Confucius and Plato among others. Real and fictional 
characters encounter each other throughout such E.L. Doctorow 
novels as ``Ragtime'' and ``Billy Bathgate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The earliest U.S. presidential biographies employed more than  
just fictional techniques -- they gave us myths. The first 
presidential ``biographer'' of any real fame was the 19th-century 
writer Parson Weems, whose concoctions included such tall tales as 
George Washington's cutting down the cherry tree. Carl Sandburg 
later had great success with his massive, romanticized biography of 
Abraham Lincoln. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent biographies have been more scholarly, but still  
controversial. In the 1960s, William Manchester was authorized by 
the Kennedys to write a book on the recently assassinated 
president, only to have the family threaten to block publication 
because he wouldn't make proposed changes. Robert Caro has been 
strongly criticized by supporters of Lyndon Johnson for his 
unflattering books about the late president's early years in 
politics. 
</P>
<P>
	Even novels about presidents have been attacked. Several critics  
and academics were enraged by Vidal's ``Lincoln,'' which was 
published in 1984 and offered a much earthier, more skeptical 
portrait than what been written before. 
</P>
<P>
	The tension between historians and writers of fiction is  
longstanding. From Herodotus in ancient Greece to Morris today, 
writers of ``non-fiction'' have been accused of treating literary 
style as a higher truth than historical fact. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, McCullough noted, historians have called for  
their peers to raise their works beyond the simple assembly of 
information. He cited a passage by the 19th-century historian 
Francis Parkman, from the introduction to ``France and England in 
North America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Faithfulness to the truth of history involves far more than  
the research, however patient and scrupulous, into special facts,'' 
Parkman wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``The narrator must seek to imbue himself with the life and  
spirit of the time. ... He must himself be, as it were, a sharer or 
a spectator of the action he describes.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 00:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
