<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harvey Threatens Fla.'s West Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEARWATER BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Tropical Storm Harvey headed for  
Florida's west coast Monday with 60 mph winds and heavy rain, 
threatening to swamp low-lying areas and beachfront hotels and 
restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm is expected to bring high winds and flooding to  
Florida's west coast as it hits land Tuesday. But many residents 
and visitors were strolling and playing on the beach, unconcerned 
about forecasts that the winds could approach hurricane strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``This one isn't really half so bad, is it?'' asked David Ray,  
whose vacation from England included a stay in Orlando last week 
during Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	That storm grazed the state's east coast as it swept from the  
Bahamas to New England -- causing dozens of deaths and massive 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 a.m. EDT Tuesday, Harvey was centered about 120 miles  
west-southwest of St. Petersburg, moving east-northeast near 9 mph. 
It took a slight turn to the south early Tuesday, but was still 
moving toward Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Maximum sustained winds increased to near 60 mph, with higher  
gusts. Tropical storm force winds of at least 39 mph extended as 
much as 205 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters expected Harvey would spin across the Florida  
peninsula and stay offshore as it heads north along the U.S. East 
Coast, sparing places like North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jeb Bush declared a state of emergency throughout Florida,  
except for the extreme northwest, in the Panhandle. 
</P>
<P>
	In Florida, a flood watch was posted for much of central,  
southwest and northeast Florida through Tuesday, including areas 
soaked last week by Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	A tropical storm warning was in effect for much of the western  
Florida coast, while a Hurricane watch remained in effect from just 
south of Fort Meyers to the mouth of the Suwannee River north of 
Tampa. 
</P>
<P>
	Voluntary evacuations were called Monday afternoon in counties  
in the storm's path. Rainfall totals of 5 to 10 inches were likely. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvey could produce storm surge flooding of 3 to 6 feet above  
normal, up to 8 feet above normal at the heads of bays, said 
hurricane center forecasters. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Bermuda's government issued a hurricane warning for  
the island Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 a.m., Gert was 200 miles south-southeast of Bermuda and  
moving to the north-northwest at about 12 mph. Top sustained winds 
were at 110 mph, with some weakening expected in the next 24 hours. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
