<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mixed Tuesday, with  
prices surging in Tokyo and Malaysia, but slipping in Hong Kong and 
Singapore. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained  
357.53 points, or 2.04 percent, to close at 17,932.79. On Monday, 
the average closed up 232.99 points, or 1.34 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo stocks rose as traders awaited the Bank of Japan's  
decision on monetary policy. The market closed before the 
announcement was made. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had said a decision to ease monetary policy could curb  
upward pressure on the Japanese yen -- a boon for Japan's exporters 
-- if it helped lower long-term interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar fell after the Japanese  
central bank decided to leave its monetary policy unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	This took financial markets by surprise, as many had predicted  
the bank would opt for an easing in a bid to halt the yen's rise 
against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 105.42 yen, down 2.50 yen from late  
Monday in Tokyo and below its late New York level of 106.38 yen 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kuala Lumpur, the key index surged 4.1 percent as Malaysia  
further eased its controversial capital controls on Tuesday by 
simplifying an exit tax for foreigners who take their profits out 
of the local stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank Negara, the Malaysian central bank, announced that the  
10-percent flat tax on profits would be implemented immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	This meant that all profits from funds brought into the country  
on or after Feb. 15 are now subject to a levy of 10 percent, 
regardless of when the profits are repatriated, Bank Negara said. 
</P>
<P>
	This system replaces a more stringent and complicated two-tier  
exit levy put in place in February. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's Composite Index rose 29.27  
points to close at 739.30. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korean shares also closed sharply higher as a powerful  
earthquake in Taiwan spurred investors to buy stocks of 
semiconductor and petrochemical companies as many of these local 
firms compete directly with many of their Taiwanese counterparts, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 23.54 points, or 2.5  
percent, to 957.42. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks closed slightly lower on profit-taking.  
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, fell 51.91 points, or 0.3 percent, closing at 
13,420.46. On Monday, the index had slipped 12.47 points, or 0.09 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said investors took profits on renewed worries over a  
possible rise in interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were also concerned about the Hong Kong government's  
plans to launch mutual funds next month to sell some of the massive 
shareholdings it acquired when it intervened in the market last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Singapore fell in listless trading. The  
benchmark Straits Times Index fell 13.89 points, or 0.6 percent, to 
2,109.04. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower. The NZSE-40  
Capital Index fell 25.86 points, or 1.2 percent, to 2,084.94. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher, boosted by  
bargain-hunting. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index 
rose 20.79 points, or 1 percent, to 2,126.54. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed lower, dragged down  
by weak resource-related stock prices. The All Ordinaries Index 
fell 8.5 points, or 3 percent, to 2,898.8. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian share prices closed higher following a late  
rally. The Composite Index rose 3.931 points, or 0.7 percent, to 
547.264. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed lower following the release on  
Monday of lower-than-expected second-quarter gross domestic product 
data. The Stock Exchange of Thailand, or SET, index fell 8.67 
points, or 1.99 percent, to 425.54. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
