<DOCNO> APW19990921.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 06:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minister Beaten, Burned to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- A real estate lawyer for three  
decades, William B. Petty Jr. yearned to follow his higher calling. 
Three years ago, he left the legal world for the ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	Petty proudly became an ordained pastor in June 1998 and was  
assigned to five small, struggling congregations in the Meigs 
County area north of Chattanooga. 
</P>
<P>
	The 56-year-old minister was still wearing his class ring from  
Emory University's Candler School of Theology when his body was 
found Saturday. He had been beaten to death with a chunk of wood 
and his body set afire. 
</P>
<P>
	Petty had been so badly burned that authorities needed his ring  
to help make the identification. His car was found Monday in 
Andrews, N.C., about 30 miles from the remote area where his 
smoldering remains were found. 
</P>
<P>
	No motive for the crime has been determined.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can't think of anyone who knew my uncle who would want to do  
him harm,'' said Petty's niece, Rose Taylor Womac. ``He was one of 
the kindest men who had ever lived. This had to have been someone 
who didn't know him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A graduate of the University of Tennessee-Knoxville School of  
Law, Petty opened a Chattanooga office and ran a real estate title 
practice. But he yearned for a different profession, Womac said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Throughout his practice of law he still had this vision of  
being a minister and being involved in church,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney John Cavett, Petty's former partner, was just a few  
months out of law school when Petty took a chance and invited him 
to join his practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the kind of guy who, if you were moving, he would want  
to show up and help you move,'' Cavett said. ``He was just such a 
good and compassionate man that it did not surprise me that he 
decided to go into the ministry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Petty decided to pursue his dream of joining the  
clergy, enrolling at Emory and earning his master's degree. On a 
profile he submitted to the school, he explained his decision: 
</P>
<P>
	``I love preaching. I love being with the people,'' he wrote.  
</P>
<P>
	Petty became an ordained pastor in June 1998 and was responsible  
for five small, struggling congregations in the Meigs County area 
north of Chattanooga. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was so loving and caring. He was always trying to help  
people,'' said the Rev. Mary Virginia Taylor, who oversees the 
district where Petty preached. ``He might have picked somebody up 
out there to work. He might have come across somebody. He was not 
afraid of people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About three months ago, Petty purchased the property where he  
and his wife, an avid hiker and outdoorswoman, planned to build a 
home for their retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	The site sits at the foot of Star Mountain, about 60 miles  
northeast of Chattanooga. ``It was a kind of utopia for him and my 
aunt as well,'' Womac said. ``They were trying to keep it as 
undisturbed as possible.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
