<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Studies Mutual Fund Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Competition among the thousands of mutual funds  
available to investors has led some fund managers to use less than 
scrupulous methods to gain attention. 
</P>
<P>
	One tried and true practice -- that of inflating a new fund's  
performance record by salting it with hot initial public offering 
stocks -- has recently come under fire from the Securities and 
Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an old game that mutual fund companies have been playing  
for years,'' said Jim Melcher, president of Balestra Capital 
Management, a New York money management firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, the SEC fined Van Kampen Funds $100,000 for  
failing to tell investors that the extraordinary first-year 
performance of Van Kampen's Growth Fund was due primarily to Van 
Kampen's liberal allocation of hot IPO stocks into the fund. A 
former Van Kampen employee, Alan Sachtleben, who served as the 
chief adviser to the fund, was also fined $25,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Kampen and Sachtleben agreed to settle the case, the first  
of its kind brought by the SEC against a mutual fund family, 
without admitting wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC has said it will continue to crack down on fund  
companies that mislead investors as to how a fund generated 
significant profits. 
</P>
<P>
	In another method for ``juicing performance,'' managers actively  
trade shares within a given fund as they try to take advantage of 
short-term movements in stock prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Both methods are used to puff up the gains of small, startup  
funds, known in the business as incubator funds, which companies 
create to generate a performance track record that is later used to 
market the fund to a wide array of investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The methods themselves are legal, experts note. But the returns  
they generate tend to be temporary and thus misleading to 
unsuspecting investors 
</P>
<P>
	David Masters, a senior analyst at Standard &AMP; Poors in New York,  
said the fine levied against Van Kampen sends a message to the 
industry that potential investors need to know whether a fund's 
advertised returns were achieved while the fund was incubating or 
after it was opened to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors who are drawn to a new fund by claims of huge early  
returns should be extremely wary, fund experts say, because it's 
highly unlikely the fund can achieve similar returns over the 
long-term. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case against Van Kampen, the Oakbrook, Ill.,-based  
company was accused of seeding its new Growth Fund with IPO shares 
while the fund held less than $380,000, tiny by mutual fund 
standards. Because the fund was so small, its overall performance 
was easily affected by the performance of a small handful of 
high-flying stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	When Van Kampen marketed its Growth Fund to the public, the  
company claimed the fund grew 62 percent in 1996, its first year. 
But the company failed to mention that the gains were achieved by 
using highly volatile IPO shares, according to the SEC. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on marketing that touted the 62 percent gain, the fund's  
assets quickly grew to $110 million after it was opened for wide 
public investing in early 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Melcher said large mutual fund companies frequently get shares  
of hot IPOs from the investment banks that underwrite new offerings 
because the fund companies are big customers of the banks' trading 
arms. ``It's a gift,'' he said. ``It's a guaranteed profit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fund managers can either spread the IPO shares across several  
funds, or place most of the shares into one small fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Unscrupulous managers tend to choose the latter, Melcher  
explained, because small funds are more susceptible to IPO 
increases, a dynamic that essentially guarantees that the fund will 
far outpace most indexes used to gauge mutual fund performance. 
</P>
<P>
	And mutual funds are all about performance, Melcher added.  
``Overwhelmingly, people who buy mutual funds look at their 
performance records. What else do they have?'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
