<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Copes With NYC Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- When police on motorcycles clear a path  
for your limousine, you don't have the traffic worries that most 
commuters face. 
</P>
<P>
	But on a rainy day in New York City, when traffic was  
particularly horrid, President Clinton said he is thinking ahead to 
the time when he will be both a New Yorker and a frustrated 
motorist. 
</P>
<P>
	``I plan to be at least part of the time a future resident of  
New York,'' Clinton said Tuesday as he toasted the General Assembly 
at U.N. headquarters in New York. ``When I move here I can complain 
about all the traffic,'' he said to laughter. 
</P>
<P>
	The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton are buying a  
post-White House home in suburban Westchester County, N.Y. Mrs. 
Clinton needs an address in the state if she is to run next year 
for a New York seat in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he knows New York's notorious traffic tangles  
sometimes will ``keep me from my appointed rounds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, he said, ``If I get very upset, I may even write a letter  
to my United States senator.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
