<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Jail Terms for Caged Girl's Mom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHILTON, Wis. (AP) -- A woman jailed for child abuse that  
included putting her daughter in a dog cage received more prison 
terms, though no more actual time to serve. 
</P>
<P>
	Circuit Judge Steven W. Winke ordered Monday that Angeline  
Rogers serve three 10-year terms on top of her current 10 years but 
that the time be concurrent, despite her escape while on work 
release earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	District Attorney Ken Kratz criticized the decision, noting that  
Rogers could have been given another 30 years in prison if Winke 
had ordered the terms to be served consecutively. 
</P>
<P>
	``She got nothing today. Not one additional day,'' Kratz said.  
``It is not even a slap on the wrist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Rogers and her husband, Michael, were each sentenced last  
September to a year in jail on one of four counts of child abuse. 
At the time, Winke stayed their 10-year sentences and sentencing on 
three other counts of child abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mrs. Rogers disappeared March 30 with a former cellmate and  
received an additional 10 years after she was found April 9 in San 
Antonio, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	She could receive more time Wednesday, when she is sentenced for  
the escape. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple was convicted of abusing four of their five children,  
including locking their 7-year-old daughter in a dog cage in 1997 
because of behavior and psychological problems, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said Mrs. Rogers wasn't a threat to the public and was  
``self-destructive,'' Kratz said. Michael Rogers is scheduled for 
release this month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
