<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Y2K Won't Interrupt Oil Deliveries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela, the world's third largest  
oil exporter and one of the main suppliers of oil to the United 
States, insists supplies won't be interrupted by the Year 2000 
computer bug. 
</P>
<P>
	But officials say isolated problems with some sectors such as  
electricity are likely to crop up, and some fear that could spill 
over to the South American nation's massive oil industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week the U.S. State Department said it was concerned about  
the so-called Y2K problem in numerous countries including 
Venezuela, which provides about 17 percent of U.S. oil imports and 
competes with Saudi Arabia and Mexico as the No. 1 exporter of oil 
to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Y2K bug stems from computers that will not function properly  
starting New Year's Day because they won't be able to distinguish 
2000 from 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	Gustavo Mendez, head of a presidential commission handling the  
Y2K problem, acknowledged Venezuela had a late start addressing the 
issue because of a change in administrations in February. But he 
said it has caught up. 
</P>
<P>
	``Venezuela guarantees the permanent delivery of oil,  
absolutely,'' Mendez told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department report, he added, was probably based on  
outdated information. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez named the presidential  
commission in April, and 15 full-time experts were immediately 
assigned to a nationwide team. Previously, the team was made up of 
people who were not dedicated to the problem full-time since they 
had other duties. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuela has also rushed in experts from the United States to  
help out. As a whole the country of 23 million people has spent 
between $600 and $800 million to fix the Y2K problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Mendez said critical systems at Venezuela's state oil monopoly,  
Petroleos de Venezuela, the world's third largest oil company, are 
100 percent surveyed, corrected and tested. That means the industry 
should have no problems come Jan. 1, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil industry analyst Alan Viergutz largely agreed, saying he  
expects no major disruption of supplies. However, he added that 
there could be some minor problems because of failures of outside 
companies and services that Petroleos de Venezuela depends on. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though most Venezuelan electricity companies say they are  
ready to go, some may have trouble, Mendez said. They are located 
on the popular tourist island of Margarita and in eastern Bolivar 
state, home to rain forests, Indian tribes, rich gold deposits and 
the massive Guri hydroelectric dam, which supplies 70 percent of 
Venezuela's electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	Glitches may also occur in central Carabobo and Aragua states,  
the heart of the industrial belt of Latin America's fourth largest 
economy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 10:00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brit Farmers Said barely Holding On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British farmers are ``holding onto survival by  
their fingertips'' as they weather the worst agricultural 
depression since the 1930s, according to a survey released today. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Farmers' Union audit found 64 percent of British  
farmers surveyed had recently borrowed money to stay afloat and 
that one-third had been forced to lay off staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``All that we need to buy is going up and everything that we  
sell is going down in price,'' said one of the 5,000 farmers who 
responded to the NFU's Audit for Action. 
</P>
<P>
	Three-quarters of the respondents said they had no confidence in  
the future of farming and 57 percent have ``seriously considered'' 
getting out of the business altogether in the past two years, the 
audit said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 40 percent said they could survive only one more year  
without improvements, and two-thirds said their children had no 
intention of taking over the farm even if things did improve. 
</P>
<P>
	NFU president Bill Gill described the industry as ``shattered to  
the core.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is no way for an important sector of the U.K. economy to  
be forced to exist at the close of the 20th century,'' Gill said. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings come one day after the British government promised  
a $245 million rescue package for farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill said the aid package would relieve some of the symptoms,  
but maintained the government hadn't addressed the causes. 
</P>
<P>
	``A reduction in the overvalued pound and the stripping away of  
the overregulation and bureaucracy choking the industry would have 
a huge impact,'' he said. ``For many farmers, this will be the 
government's last chance to act.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
