<HEADLINE> Barak Makes Symbolic Trip to Berlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- In a visit rich in symbolism, Israeli Prime  
Minister Ehud Barak was welcomed in Berlin on Tuesday as the first 
foreign leader to visit the German capital since the government 
returned to the former seat of Nazi power. 
</P>
<P>
	The visit -- just weeks after Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder left  
Bonn and started work in Berlin -- was intended to demonstrate 
Germany's sensitivity to the discomfort some might feel at seeing 
the nation governed once more from Hitler's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``Berlin evokes deep emotions in our consciousness,'' Barak told  
reporters at Schroeder's provisional office in central Berlin. ``It 
is not far from here that the Final Solution was devised in 1942.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barak spoke about dramatic changes in the last two generations --  
changes that have led to ``close ties between a new, vibrant, 
democratic Germany and the state of Israel that arose out of the 
ashes of the Holocaust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder, for his part, said Germany's place in the  
international community ``can only be preserved if the past is not 
forgotten and not distorted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the emotional highlight of the trip, Schroeder was to join  
Barak in the commemoration of Holocaust victims Wednesday at the 
former Sachsenhausen concentration camp north of Berlin. The 
leaders were to lay a wreath at the site, where the Nazis once 
cremated camp victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Traveling with Barak were several Sachsenhausen survivors who  
now live in Israel. One, 82-year-old Eli Carmel, spent a year in 
the camp. 
</P>
<P>
	His visit, he said, was like ``a circle closing -- having been a  
homeless, stateless Jew and coming back with the prime minister of 
our Jewish state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the visit should send a clear message: ``Never forget  
what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Nazis held more than 200,000 people at Sachsenhausen between  
1933 and 1945. About half died, including an estimated 10,000 Jews 
and 18,000 Soviet soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	As always when the Israeli premier travels, the Middle East  
peace process was at the top of the agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak's visit comes just a week after Israel and the  
Palestinians launched final status peace talks. This last phase 
aims to resolve the most contentious issues: borders, the return of 
Palestinian refugees, and the status of Jerusalem. 
</P>
<P>
	The Europeans have been buoyed by the resumption of talks and by  
Barak's impressive -- if somewhat hopeful -- deadlines: a framework 
for a deal by February, and a final deal by September 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak said he'd briefed Schroeder on the progress of the talks.  
He said he hoped, ``with the peace process gaining more momentum, 
that Germany will expand its role.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much more active in the peace process than the Germans, however,  
are the French, who aim to carve out a bigger role for themselves 
as a counterweight to American influence. Barak heads to Paris 
later this week for talks with President Jacques Chirac and Prime 
Minister Lionel Jospin. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the weekend, Chirac held an unexpected meeting with Syrian  
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa. France and Syria have good 
relations, and al-Sharaa apparently wanted Chirac to assess 
Israel's willingness to withdraw from the Golan Heights, which it 
captured in 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	Peace talks between Israel and Syria have been stalled since  
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about peace with Syria, Barak said, ``It is time.''  
</P>
<P>
	``I believe there is a golden opportunity right now,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
