<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers' Coach: Offense Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- After seven weeks of coaching and cramming,  
teaching and learning, practicing and practicing some more, the 
Pittsburgh Steelers finally seem comfortable with Kevin Gilbride's 
new offense. 
</P>
<P>
	More importantly, coach Bill Cowher said Tuesday, the offensive  
coordinator seems to be getting comfortable with his new players. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kevin is getting a sense of the players, what to do best with  
Kordell Stewart, our receivers, the running game,'' Cowher said. 
``It's not just players getting comfortable with the system, it's 
also Kevin with the players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that Cowher is entirely satisfied, even with a 2-0 start on  
the road that has kept the Steelers on pace with AFC Central 
favorite Jacksonville. The Steelers play their home opener Sunday 
against Seattle (1-1). 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're adapting, no question. We're getting more  
comfortable, no doubt about it,'' Cowher said. ``Obviously, the 
consistency level we're performing at, we need to get better. I 
like where we're going with it. We just need more consistency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cowher liked how the Steelers moved the ball at the beginning  
and end of Sunday's 23-20 victory in Baltimore. But the offense 
bogged down in the third quarter and, while not turning over the 
ball, totaled a relatively low 270 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	There is another nagging concern: injuries.  
</P>
<P>
	Running back Jerome Bettis, held to 46 yards by Baltimore, has a  
hamstring injury only a week after recovering from knee and calf 
problems. Bettis, who said Monday he was extremely sore after 
Sunday's game, is listed as questionable. He won't practice 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Left guard Alan Faneca (ankle, probable) and right tackle Chris  
Conrad (knee, questionable) also left Sunday's game with injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The offense has made some mistakes as it adjusts to Gilbride's  
schemes, which require the quarterback, receivers and blockers to 
read formations identically. The receivers adjust their pass routes 
to the coverage, and the quarterback must make the same reads. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to take the players you have, put them in a  
position where they can make plays, but at the same time not 
deviate too much from a philosophy,'' Cowher said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers also are constantly switching their third-down  
alignments. Tight end Mark Bruener sometimes comes out of the game, 
sometimes stays in. At times, there are five receivers; other 
times, there are four. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're spreading people out, doing things differently, and  
we're not as predictable, I think, as we've been,'' Cowher said. 
``Maybe we kept doing the same things over and over again; now, 
we're doing some things that maybe create indecision with the 
defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's some creativity taking place that, hopefully, is  
making the defense wonder what we're doing next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, for the first time in his career, Stewart can check off  
plays at the line of scrimmage. Stewart changed about 15 plays in 
Cleveland and about six on Sunday, according to Bettis. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're changing things at the line, getting us out of bad  
plays, getting us into good plays,'' Cowher said. ``Some we didn't 
execute, but I still like the decision-making that took place.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
