<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Y2K Won't Interrupt Oil Deliveries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela, the world's third largest  
oil exporter and one of the main suppliers of oil to the United 
States, insists supplies won't be interrupted by the Year 2000 
computer bug. 
</P>
<P>
	But officials say isolated problems with some sectors such as  
electricity are likely to crop up, and some fear that could spill 
over to the South American nation's massive oil industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week the U.S. State Department said it was concerned about  
the so-called Y2K problem in numerous countries including 
Venezuela, which provides about 17 percent of U.S. oil imports and 
competes with Saudi Arabia and Mexico as the No. 1 exporter of oil 
to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Y2K bug stems from computers that will not function properly  
starting New Year's Day because they won't be able to distinguish 
2000 from 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	Gustavo Mendez, head of a presidential commission handling the  
Y2K problem, acknowledged Venezuela had a late start addressing the 
issue because of a change in administrations in February. But he 
said it has caught up. 
</P>
<P>
	``Venezuela guarantees the permanent delivery of oil,  
absolutely,'' Mendez told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department report, he added, was probably based on  
outdated information. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez named the presidential  
commission in April, and 15 full-time experts were immediately 
assigned to a nationwide team. Previously, the team was made up of 
people who were not dedicated to the problem full-time since they 
had other duties. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuela has also rushed in experts from the United States to  
help out. As a whole the country of 23 million people has spent 
between $600 and $800 million to fix the Y2K problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Mendez said critical systems at Venezuela's state oil monopoly,  
Petroleos de Venezuela, the world's third largest oil company, are 
100 percent surveyed, corrected and tested. That means the industry 
should have no problems come Jan. 1, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil industry analyst Alan Viergutz largely agreed, saying he  
expects no major disruption of supplies. However, he added that 
there could be some minor problems because of failures of outside 
companies and services that Petroleos de Venezuela depends on. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though most Venezuelan electricity companies say they are  
ready to go, some may have trouble, Mendez said. They are located 
on the popular tourist island of Margarita and in eastern Bolivar 
state, home to rain forests, Indian tribes, rich gold deposits and 
the massive Guri hydroelectric dam, which supplies 70 percent of 
Venezuela's electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	Glitches may also occur in central Carabobo and Aragua states,  
the heart of the industrial belt of Latin America's fourth largest 
economy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 04:40:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Maine Potato Farmers Begin Harvest / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The 1990s have been bleak for Maine's potato farmers. Neighbors  
watched nervously as the potato prices plummeted because of a 
nationwide glut. Banks began auctioning off generations-old farms. 
</P>
<P>
	But now there's hope.  
</P>
<P>
	Farmers and their helpers poured into the fields this week to  
begin harvesting a crop described as ``tremendous.'' Also, the 
state's total acreage for potatoes climbed instead of decreasing 
for the first time in years. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a real optimism here,'' said Don Flannery, associate  
executive director of the Maine Potato Board. ``That being said, we 
are realists, too. We know our competition in Canada and 
nationwide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers in northern Maine managed to avoid the effects of the  
East Coast drought this summer. They are banking on a bumper year 
after near-perfect weather. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maine has been very fortunate in Aroostook County in that  
they've had timely showers and it's made for an excellent crop,'' 
said Maine Agriculture Commissioner Bob Spear. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in land devoted to potatoes from 65,000 acres last  
year to 68,000 acres this year was partly because of demand from 
McCain Foods USA, the world's largest french fry producer, Flannery 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, based in Oakbrook, Ill., is completing a $70 million  
expansion of its french fry processing plant in Easton this fall. 
It has four other processing plants in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Yaeger, sales manager at H. Smith Packing in Blaine,  
called McCain's expansion a ``vote of confidence in the Maine 
potato grower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it is more than a just morale boost.  
</P>
<P>
	Because of the reliability in the french fry and potato chip  
market, more and more farmers are shifting their crops from the 
types of potatoes sold in grocery stores to potatoes that are more 
suited to processing. 
</P>
<P>
	Processing potatoes are considered to be less susceptible to  
market conditions than ``tablestock'' because farmers enter into 
contracts with processors like McCain, Frito Lay and Humpty Dumpty 
Potato Chip Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, 54 percent of the crop was dedicated to french fries  
and potato chips, 19 percent went to tablestock and the remaining 
27 percent was harvested for seed, according to the Maine Potato 
Board. 
</P>
<P>
	That's good news for Aroostook County and a state where potatoes  
are the No. 1 agricultural commodity, with annual sales of nearly 
$105 million. Maine ranked eighth in the nation in potato 
production last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all farmers are confident, however.  
</P>
<P>
	Mark Nightingale, whose grandfather started his farm in New  
Limerick, says it's a slow road to economic recovery in Aroostook 
County and not everyone is out of the red. 
</P>
<P>
	``People here are still struggling and there isn't much help,''  
said Nightingale, who reduced his potato crop to 380 acres this 
year and increased his wheat production, planting 400 acres of 
grain. 
</P>
<P>
	He acknowledged that because of the weather in northern Maine  
this summer, this crop should be particularly good in terms of 
quality. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had just enough water and we've had an unusually warm  
year,'' said Jim Cook, director of Crown of Maine Organic 
Cooperative, in Madawaska. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
