<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Proposes Abortion Alternatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government would spend $85 million  
a year to help pay for facilities that provide alternatives to 
abortion -- maternity homes, adoption services and crisis pregnancy 
centers -- under legislation proposed Tuesday by two conservative 
members of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Joseph Pitts and Sen. Rick Santorum, both Pennsylvania  
Republicans, said the grants would not be available to family 
planning centers or other agencies that refer women to abortion 
providers, provide abortion counseling or perform abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	The centers would use the money to help women dealing with an  
unplanned pregnancy, including pregnancy testing, adoption 
information, prenatal and postpartum health care, diapers, baby 
food and clothes, abstinence counseling and referrals for other 
services -- help with problems with mental health, food, clothing, 
housing, education and job training. 
</P>
<P>
	Poorer women would be given first priority. Federal money would  
be allocated to each state based on the number of abortions and 
out-of-wedlock births there. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitts and Santorum said the legislation is needed to provide  
alternatives to government family planning programs that seem to 
focus on abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	``No women should ever feel that abortion is her only option,''  
Santorum said. ``Not everyone who walks into a family planning 
clinic wants to have an abortion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The National Abortion Federation immediately attacked the bill,  
saying it ``poses a significant public health danger because it 
would support organizations that withhold information about safe, 
legal options to unintended pregnancy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Group Executive Director Vicki Saporta said abortion providers  
are skilled medical professionals who discuss abortion alternatives 
with their patients. ``Under this bill someone with a political or 
religious agenda who erroneously informs a woman that she has only 
one option would receive funding, while a skilled health care 
professional who informs her of all her options would not.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
