<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World-Herald Buying Newspaper Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- The Omaha World-Herald Co. announced Tuesday  
it is buying Partnership Press Inc., a newspaper company co-founded 
by former NBC News President Michael Gartner. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase is expected to close Sept. 30. Terms were not  
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition includes The Tribune, a Pulitzer Prize-winning  
newspaper in Ames, Iowa, that has a circulation of 10,200. 
</P>
<P>
	Partnership Press also owns several weekly papers in central  
Iowa, including The Algona Upper Des Moines, Nevada Journal, Boone 
Today, Dallas County News and Tri-County Times. Its other holdings 
include shopping guides and direct mail businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Gartner, chairman of Partnership Press, won the 1997 Pulitzer  
Prize for editorial writing at The Tribune. He is a former editor 
of The Des Moines Register. 
</P>
<P>
	He founded Partnership Press in 1986 with Gary Gerlach and David  
Belin, a Des Moines lawyer who died in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``From the beginning Gary and I emphasized good journalism,''  
Gartner said. ``World-Herald executives are committed to good 
journalism, and they are particularly devoted to the Midwest as a 
region.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Gottschalk, chairman and president of the employee-owned  
Omaha World-Herald Co., said central Iowa is ``a wonderful 
marketplace with a good mix of higher education, agriculture, 
manufacturing, technology businesses and government institutions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gottschalk said he did not expect many changes at The Tribune or  
the other publications, calling them ``solid operations'' that 
should continue to grow. 
</P>
<P>
	The Omaha World-Herald Co. owns the World-Herald, which has a  
daily circulation of 220,000, and three other dailies: The Record 
in Stockton, Calif., the Kearney (Neb.) Hub and the Carlsbad (N.M.) 
Current-Argus. The company also owns four weeklies in Nebraska: the 
Papillion Times, the Ralston Recorder, the Bellevue Leader and the 
Air Pulse, which serves Offutt Air Force Base. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also owns direct marketing operations in Dallas,  
Chicago, Atlanta and Omaha and two exposition management companies, 
and has interests in election services, investment banking and 
Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Hawley was named president of Partnership Press and  
publisher of the Ames paper, replacing Gerlach. Hawley, 41, is a 
native Iowan who was publisher of the Huron (S.D.) Plainsman from 
1996 until earlier this year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
