<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Trade Surplus Falls in Aug. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's trade surplus with the world fell in August  
from the same month last year, the government said Wednesday. But 
the politically sensitive trade surplus with the United States 
continued to rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The merchandise trade surplus, the measure of all goods exported  
by Japan minus those imported, declined 22.6 percent to $6.57 
billion (689.4 billion yen), the Finance Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	The surplus, unadjusted for seasonal factors, slightly exceeded  
the average forecast of $6.55 billion by Tokyo-based economists 
surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires. 
</P>
<P>
	Again bucking the overall trend, however was the trade surplus  
with the United States, which jumped 24.3 percent in August to 
$5.09 billion, the ministry said. In July, the surplus rose 8.0 
percent from the same month a year earlier, while in June it was up 
18.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan, fighting to emerge from its worst downturn in 50 years,  
has been under heavy pressure from the United States and other 
trading partners to rein in the surplus by bolstering its weak 
economy to spark demand for imports. 
</P>
<P>
	August marked the fifth straight month of year-on-year decline  
in the overall surplus. In July it fell 4.6 percent, which followed 
declines of 2.9 percent in June, 31.5 percent in May and 12.6 
percent in April. 
</P>
<P>
	In fiscal 1998, Japan's overall trade surplus rose 23 percent  
from the previous year to reach the second highest total ever 
recorded. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
