<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Calls Microsoft a Monopoly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government wrapped up its historic  
antitrust trial Tuesday against the Microsoft Corp., its lawyers 
accusing the company in closing arguments of acting as a vigilant 
monopolist intent on squelching upstart rivals at the expense of 
consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, which was also to make its closing arguments Tuesday,  
said in a midday statement that the government ``truly has blinders 
on when it looks at what is going on in the high-tech industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday was the last time lawyers were meeting in the courtroom  
prior to U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's first of a 
two-phase verdict. That decision could come as early as next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing dozens of internal e-mails and sworn testimony,  
government lawyers portrayed Microsoft as ruthless in its efforts 
to protect the dominance of its lucrative Windows software. 
Microsoft's flagship product runs most personal computers and is 
largely responsible for the vast wealth of the world's richest man, 
billionaire company Chairman Bill Gates. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no other lawful situations in which a company has  
done what Microsoft has done,'' Justice Department lawyer David 
Boies said, adding that the company ``used its power to squelch 
potential competitors, to keep them from emerging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Houck, the lead lawyer for 19 states suing Microsoft  
with the federal government, told the judge that the company's 
``unshakable stranglehold'' over such software ``has cost consumers 
untold millions -- probably hundreds of millions of dollars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Microsoft is like the emperor without clothes,'' said Houck,  
who gave part of the government's tag-team closing arguments. 
``Everyone knows, including Microsoft, that it's a monopoly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judge was unusually quiet Tuesday, offering no insights into  
how he is formulating his decision. He sat through two hours of 
arguments early in the day, asking only one minor question to 
clarify the date of a particular e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Boies listed an array of budding technologies from some top  
companies in the high-tech industry that he said had failed to 
achieve full promise because of pressure from Microsoft, including 
Internet software from the former Netscape Communications Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Microsoft has gone out to smash them down,'' Boies said.  
``This is a monopolist that is very vigilant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Challenging a key defense by Microsoft lawyers, Boies said  
upstart technologies and products don't mean the company faces any 
viable competition for the software that runs computers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever happens in the future cannot vindicate what Microsoft  
has done over the years,'' Boies said, urging the judge to 
remember: ``This case is about the real world.'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
