<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> California Wildfires Spreading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A Benedictine monastery known for its tasty  
fruitcakes and stunning views of the Pacific Ocean was evacuated as 
wildfires raced up a mountain and threatened as many as 250 monks 
and visitors. 
</P>
<P>
	The mandatory evacuation order at the New Camaldoli Hermitage on  
Monday was the first caused by several active, lightning-caused 
fires that have burned through more than 72,000 acres of Northern 
California's forests. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have temporarily evacuated,'' said a message left on the  
monks' answering machine Monday night. ``We're in no immediate 
danger but they tell us it's better to keep moving. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the nonessential personnel are leaving; a few monks are  
remaining behind,'' the message said. ``God bless you. Pray for 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The monastery, perched 1,300 feet above the Pacific Ocean about  
140 miles south of San Francisco, is popular with visitors seeking 
solitary contemplation. They can rent rooms by the month. 
</P>
<P>
	Reachable only by a narrow, twisting road from the coastal  
highway, it also houses between 30 and 40 monks who maintain vows 
of silence and support their contemplative life by selling 
fruitcakes over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The monks and visitors were told to gather at Grange Hall in the  
town of Big Sur, a dozen miles up the coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Monday, the fires had not threatened people so seriously.  
</P>
<P>
	In Big Sur's Los Padres National Forest, at least 28,000 acres  
of oak trees, sage, chaparral and other brush had burned by Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 47,500 acres had burned in the Trinity Alps Wilderness  
Area about 210 miles north of San Francisco, making the wildfire 
the largest burning in the nation, fire spokeswoman Rosemary Hardin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of these mountains go straight up and down,'' said Joe  
Pasinato, a Forest Service spokesman with the firefighters in Big 
Sur. ``I don't see how you could possibly build a hand line on 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in Big Sur, a fire came within a mile of another  
religious center, Tassajara Hot Springs, which is populated by Zen 
Buddhists. Residents there were advised to either evacuate, or be 
ready to leave in a hurry. It is the off-season for tourists, so 
only a few people remained Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
