<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Apple Expects Lower Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) -- Apple Computer Inc. stock plunged this  
morning after the company disclosed that a shortage of chips used 
in its Power Mac G4 would result in an unexpected shortfall in 
fourth quarter profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said Monday that Motorola has not been able to  
supply enough chips to fill all the more than 150,000 orders Apple 
has received since announcing the product three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the company expects to report earnings of between  
$75 million and $85 million on Oct. 13, down from $106 million 
during the same quarter in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple stock tumbled as much as 10 percent in early trading today  
as investors responded to the announcement, made after the close of 
markets Monday. The stock price was down $7 a share, or $72.06 1/4, by 
mid-morning on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	The warning showed profit would equal about 43 cents to 49 cents  
per share, down from the 76 cents estimated by analysts polled by 
First Call/Thomson Financial. 
</P>
<P>
	``We regret that we will not be able to ship them all this  
quarter,'' said Apple's interim CEO Steve Jobs. ``This is a 
temporary issue, and we hope to catch up early in the coming 
quarter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The profit shortfall should not darken the longer-term outlook  
at Apple, said Dan Lavin, who follows technology companies as 
research director with IV Associates, in Burlingame, Calif. 
Analysts have simply expected too much, too quickly from Apple, 
whose core products are doing well, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've more than doubled their market share. They're finally  
making money,'' Lavin said. ``This is just a case of the analysts 
continuing to push and push and push and then they got savaged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The news is the first financial blow since Apple's announced  
recovery last October, when Jobs proudly reported the company's 
first profitable fiscal year since 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple's chief financial officer Fred Anderson said Monday that  
despite the fourth quarter glitch, the company's fiscal year will 
end with ``significant year-over-year growth in units and revenue 
in the December quarter.'' 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
