<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPORARY WORKERS: In the mid-1990s, many companies that had  
eliminated thousands of jobs in the early part of the decade turned 
to temporary or contingency help when staff positions opened up. 
That trend has continued, according to the employment consulting 
firm Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas Inc. The company, noting that the 
number of so-called alternative workers grew from 12.1 million to 
12.5 million between 1995 and 1997, said employers are finding that 
these workers are better suited for the demands posed by global 
expansion and high technology. Alternative workers include 
independent contractors, on-call workers, temporary agency 
employees and workers provided by contract firms. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MUTUAL FUND COSTS: The cost of owning a stock mutual fund  
continues to drop, according to the Investment Company Institute, a 
trade group for the mutual fund industry. A study by ICI economists 
found that the cost of fund investing fell 5.6 percent in 1998, and 
is down a cumulative 40 percent since 1980. The study looked at 
major fees, expenses and sales charges that investors pay in buying 
and owning fund shares. ICI president Matthew Fink says competition 
among mutual funds has helped bring costs down -- fund companies 
vying for investors have worked to get their own expenses down so 
they can charge their customers less and give them higher returns. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HOW TO HIRE INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY EMPLOYEES: If you're looking  
for people to run your company's information technology, you might 
want to try a different approach to hiring. Dan Tully, executive 
vice president of Conduit Systems, a consulting firm based in 
Lincoln, R.I., makes several suggestions in an article in Inc. 
Technology magazine. First: Place more importance on job 
candidates' experience rather than their education. Look for people 
who are relaxed rather than tightly wound. If you have a short-term 
plan for developing your information technology, pick a seasoned 
veteran who can give you immediate results. For a more long-term 
approach, go with a younger prospect who will have room to grow. 
Once you've made your choice, be sure you pay your employees well, 
and make vacation time mandatory to avoid burnout. Be flexible 
about work schedules, and provide workers with ongoing educational 
opportunities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
