<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Internet To Reach Poor India Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Video e-mail will open up India's  
Internet revolution next month to thousands of poor, illiterate -- 
and awestruck -- villagers who have never seen a computer. 
</P>
<P>
	On Oct. 2, the birthday of Indian independence leader Mohandas  
Gandhi, video e-mail booths will be inaugurated in eight towns in 
Uttar Pradesh and Bihar -- two of India's poorest and most populous 
states. A conglomerate of Indian computer software makers announced 
the program Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The booths, complete with video cameras, will be wired up with  
20 similar booths hundreds of miles away in Bombay, India's 
financial hub, said Dewang Mehta, who heads the National 
Association of Software and Service Companies. 
</P>
<P>
	It will cost 15 rupees -- or 35 cents -- to send or receive a  
three-minute message, including a video image and voice, through an 
e-mail account. 
</P>
<P>
	For villagers, it may take half a day to earn 15 rupees. But  
Mehta feels many would pay it for the chance to hear and see a 
loved one once in a while. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the initial users in Bombay are expected to be taxi  
drivers who left their small towns and villages to make a living in 
the faraway metropolis. They are able to visit their families only 
once a year, and regular old-fashioned mail takes weeks to reach 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	Most villages in India still do not have access to a telephone,  
and only about half of the country's population has a phone 
connection. The software makers' association hopes the Internet 
project will eventually enable millions of poor, illiterate people 
to communicate cheaply. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet connectivity is growing in India, but the global  
information revolution has so far touched only a fraction of the 
country's nearly 1 billion people. India has only 3.2 million 
personal computers, and only 400,000 Indians have access to the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The central government surrendered its Internet monopoly last  
November, offering foreign companies up to a 49 percent share in 
local joint ventures. The Communications Ministry has said it would 
provide all district hubs across the country with Internet 
connectivity, but progress has been slow. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, the 300,000 privately-owned telephone booths in the  
country are likely to provide video E-mail facilities, officials 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet is beginning to go beyond what was considered the  
elite of the city,'' Mehta told a gathering of Indian Internet 
entrepreneurs Tuesday. ``Common people who do not have a personal 
computer or a telephone can have an E-mail address.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hamilton Sundstrand To Cut Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINDSOR LOCKS, Conn. (AP) -- Hamilton Sundstrand, the aerospace  
unit of United Technologies Corp., announced plans Tuesday to cut 
1,500 jobs, a move the company called the ``natural result'' of the 
merger between Hamilton Standard and Sundstrand Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``In addition, the current aerospace and industrial sales  
declines as well as ongoing industry consolidation are continuing, 
and we are aggressively reducing our costs to meet these 
challenges,'' Hamilton Sundstrand President Ron McKenna said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said Tuesday it would close and sell the electronics  
operation at its plant in suburban Windsor Locks, and complete the 
shutdown of a plant in Colorado Springs, Colo. Other operations 
will be consolidated at Windsor Locks. 
</P>
<P>
	The job cuts, to be carried out between now and the end of 2000,  
amount to 8.3 percent of the company's work force. Hamilton 
Sundstrand was created earlier this year by the merger of Hamilton 
Standard and Rockford, Ill.-based Sundstrand Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Parent, the business director for Machinists District 91,  
said the union would begin negotiating with the company Wednesday 
on early retirement and severance packages. 
</P>
<P>
	The union also has six months to try and convince the United  
Technologies Corp. subsidiary to keep the jobs in Connecticut, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are jobs that when they leave, they will never come  
back,'' Parent told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The cutbacks will reduce the number of electronics facilities  
from six to four. The company is also closing its customer support 
facility in East Windsor, Conn., and relocating its operations to 
Windsor Locks, a move which gets the company out of a leased 
building. 
</P>
<P>
	Propeller systems overhaul and repair work now done in East  
Windsor will move to Long Beach, Calif., and Maastricht, the 
Netherlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Military spares and commercial spares operations will be  
consolidated, with the military side of the business in Windsor 
Locks and the commercial side in Rockford. Some 60 positions at 
Rockford Plant 1 will move to other facilities in Rockford, Miami, 
and Long Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Work from two other Rockford-area sites will be moved to Plant  
1. Both smaller plants will be closed and the one owned by the 
company will be sold. 
</P>
<P>
	To minimize the number of people who must be laid off, the  
company is first offering a voluntary separation package to 
salaried and hourly workers. The details of the package for hourly 
workers will have to be negotiated with the Machinists union. 
</P>
<P>
	Until the company knows how many people will take the buyout,  
the exact number of layoffs required will not be clear. Hamilton 
Sundstrand spokesman John Mayo said today the company hopes as many 
as 500 workers will take the buyout. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton Sundstrand already has cut 210 jobs this year.  
</P>
<P>
	The company has dozens of plants around the world, with 18,000  
employees and $3 billion in sales. Its products for the aerospace 
industry include electric power generation and distribution 
systems, fuel pumps, engine control systems, environmental control 
systems and propellers. 
</P>
<P>
	In August, McKenna had said he wanted to move the company away  
from making individual components and toward selling entire 
electronic, hydraulic and fuel systems to aircraft manufacturers. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 11:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Set To Prober Atlanta Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Congressional leader intends to pursue  
legislation to end the ``culture of corruption'' that pervaded 
Atlanta's winning bid for the 1996 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., said today his House commerce  
subcommittee on oversight and investigation will hold hearings next 
month on the Atlanta bid and will invite IOC president Juan Antonio 
Samaranch to testify. If Samaranch doesn't appear voluntarily, 
Upton said a subpoena is likely. 
</P>
<P>
	A report on the Atlanta bid, submitted to Congress last week by  
former attorney general Griffin Bell, shows clearly that ``votes 
were for sale, and it's got to stop,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Upton said his panel will consider ending the IOC's exemption  
from the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act as a possible way to end the 
longstanding practice of gift-giving to IOC members to influence 
the selection of host cities for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Upton announced his plans at a news conference one day after the  
U.S. Olympic Committee said it plans no further investigation of 
Atlanta's bid for the 1996 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC demanded last week the USOC explain why details of  
Atlanta's gifts, travel payments and scholarship offers were not 
included in an earlier report the USOC provided in an IOC inquiry 
into improprieties in candidate cities. 
</P>
<P>
	USOC spokesman Mike Moran told The Atlanta Journal-Constitution  
on Monday that an amended report submitted to congressional 
investigators last week ``does nothing to alter what we are clear 
about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is much wider than any American city,'' Moran said.  
</P>
<P>
	The report turned over to lawmakers by former Attorney General  
Griffin Bell, who revised it on behalf of Atlanta Olympics 
organizers, revealed that Atlanta bidders offered or considered 
lavish favors, gifts and perks for IOC members and their families, 
including college scholarships, free healthcare and job offers. 
</P>
<P>
	The report amended a previous accounting given to a U.S. House  
commerce subcommittee investigation opened in the wake of the Salt 
Lake City scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The USOC forwarded a copy of Bell's report to the IOC late last  
week. In a cover letter, an USOC attorney said the Colorado 
Springs, Colo., organization did not plan any further 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've learned all the lessons to be learned in this,'' said  
Scott Blackmon, deputy executive director and lead counsel of the 
USOC. ``Based on what we've seen in the report, it looks like more 
of the same culture. There's nothing different between what 
happened in Atlanta and Salt Lake City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some IOC members were critical of the Bell report and comments  
Atlanta officials made, in which they implied that they had been 
drawn into a climate of corruption when they began their bid to 
hold the Games in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian IOC member Mario Pescante, who led Rome's losing  
campaign for the 2004 Games, accused the Americans of ducking 
responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why don't the Americans take the responsibility for the people  
who organized this strategy of bribery and corruption? Who started 
this? They did,'' Pescante told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Moran said the USOC would not be drawn into finger-pointing.  
</P>
<P>
	``The question of whether cities are forcing something on IOC  
members or whether IOC members are soliciting gifts is not the 
point,'' Moran said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the USOC's own probe ``made it clear there is a culture  
of this involving all bid cities and the IOC itself. It has ebbed 
and flowed in various cities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten IOC members either resigned or were expelled in connection  
with the Salt Lake City vote-buying scandal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
