<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Sept. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gov't Calls Microsoft a Monopoly  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government wrapped up its historic  
antitrust trial against the Microsoft Corp., today. Its lawyers 
accused the company in closing arguments of acting as a vigilant 
monopolist intent on squelching upstart rivals at the expense of 
consumers. Microsoft, which was also to make its closing arguments 
today, said in a midday statement that the government ``truly has 
blinders on when it looks at what is going on in the high-tech 
industry.'' Today was the last time lawyers were meeting in the 
courtroom prior to U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's 
first part of a two-phase verdict. That decision could come as 
early as next month. Microsoft stock was down 2 5/16 at 95 1/4 in 
afternoon trading. 

</P>
<P>
	Apple Expects Lower Earnings  
</P>
<P>
	CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) -- Apple Computer Inc. stock was down 7  
15/16 at 71 1/8 this afternoon ell today after the company disclosed 
that a shortage of chips used in its Power Mac G4 would result in 
an unexpected shortfall in fourth quarter profits. The company said 
late yesterday that Motorola has not been able to supply enough 
chips to fill all the more than 150,000 orders Apple has received 
since announcing the product three weeks ago. As a result, the 
company expects to report earnings of between $75 million and $85 
million on Oct. 13, down from $106 million during the same quarter 
in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Trade Deficit Swells in July  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. trade deficit ballooned to a monthly  
record of $25.2 billion in July as a flood of foreign cars, 
machinery and consumer goods pushed imports to an all-time high. 
The U.S. deficit with Japan, China and Western Europe all set 
records. The Commerce Department reported today that the trade 
deficit grew by 2.4 percent in July, surpassing the June imbalance 
of $24.6 billion. The growing deficit was seen as contributing to 
today's fall in stock prices on Wall Street. The U.S. trade 
imbalance has climbed to new highs for seven straight months, 
pushing the gap between imports and exports to an annual rate of 
$247 billion, far above last year's record deficit of $164.3 
billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Sink; Dow Down 182.05  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply and steadily today amid  
increasing concerns about the weakening dollar, the growing U.S. 
trade deficit and the upcoming earnings season. Just before 3 p.m. 
EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 182.05 at 10,641.85. 
Broader stock indicators also fell, with the Nasdaq composite down 
40.99 at 2,845.16. Although the markets fell throughout the day, 
analysts said the selloff was a calm one, mostly growing out of the 
uncertainties raised by recent economic news. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EDT:  
Dow Industrials:        10641.85 - 182.05
NYSE Issues:         Advances  681  Declines 2278  Unchgd  512
