</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs Profits Beat Forecast  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Driven by a strong overseas presence, Goldman  
Sachs Group Inc. beat Wall Street's predictions with profits that 
soared 94 percent in its third fiscal quarter. The investment bank 
on today posted net income of $638 million, or $1.31 a share, for 
the quarter ended Aug. 27, easily beating analysts' estimates of 
$1.09. Goldman earned pro forma profits of $329 million, or 69 
cents a share in the third quarter last year, when the company was 
still privately held. The latest three-month period marked 
Goldman's first full quarter as a publicly-held company. Goldman 
Sachs was down 1 1/2 at 59 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Hamilton Sundstrand To Cut Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Hamilton Sundstrand, the aerospace unit  
of United Technologies Corp., plans to cut some 1,500 jobs, or 
about 8.3 percent of its work force, between now and the end of 
2000. The company said today it would close and sell the 
electronics operation at its plant in suburban Windsor Locks, and 
complete the shutdown of a plant in Colorado Springs, Colo. Other 
operations will be consolidated at Windsor Locks. 

</P>
<P>
	FDA Approves New Antibiotic  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government today approved a long-needed  
new weapon against the growing threat of drug-resistant bacteria: 
Synercid, the first alternative in 30 years to the antibiotic of 
last resort. The new drug comes at a critical time, as doctors are 
warning that more and more germs are developing resistance to that 
``silver bullet'' antibiotic, vancomycin. The FDA for the past year 
has allowed hundreds of patients at risk of death from 
drug-resistant germs to be treated with Synercid under a special 
emergency program. Today, the FDA approved Synercid to treat 
vancomycin-resistant enterococcal infections, a life-threatening 
infection that typically strikes hospital patients. 

</P>
<P>
	Michelin Workers Protest Layoffs  
</P>
<P>
	CLERMONT-FERRAND, France (AP) -- More than 1,000 Michelin workers  
and union activists rallied outside the tire giant's headquarters 
today to protest a plan to cut 7,500 jobs despite higher profits. 
Michelin, based in this central French city, announced Sept. 8 that 
it would cut 7,500 jobs over the next three years, reducing the 
company's European work force by about 10 percent. The company said 
it also aims to increase productivity by at least 20 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Britain Holds Second Gold Sale  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The Bank of England conducted its second gold sale  
today, disposing of 25 metric tons of British reserves at slightly 
more than the market price. The sale, the second this year, fetched 
$255.75 per troy ounce. The opening bid price in London this 
morning was $255.20. World gold prices have declined markedly since 
the Treasury announced its sale intention in May. Gold fell about 
$6 to $282.40 per troy ounce on May 7, the day the sale was 
announced. 

</P>
<P>
	Thailand: No More IMF Help Needed  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- The Thai government said today that it  
will not need to draw the remaining $3 billion from a $17 billion 
rescue fund established by the International Monetary Fund to bail 
out its battered economy. The declaration came in an official 
communication to the IMF approved by the Cabinet at its weekly 
meeting today. 

</P>
<P>
	Vodafone, Bell Atlantic To Ally  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bell Atlantic, the nation's largest local  
telephone company, reached agreement to acquire the U.S. mobile 
phone network of Vodafone AirTouch PLC in a deal that will create a 
wireless communications company that will be able to serve 90 
percent of the U.S. population. In exchange for Vodafone's $15 
billion wireless network, Bell Atlantic will give Vodafone a 45 
percent stake in the new company, under the deal announced today. 
Bell Atlantic will manage the New York-based venture with assets of 
$28 billion, and control a majority of seats on the new board. 

</P>
<P>
	Unilever To Cut Brand Portfolio  
</P>
<P>
	ROTTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Anglo-Dutch consumer products  
conglomerate Unilever NV plans to cut its brand portfolio to a core 
of 400 products from its current 1,600 brands. Unilever, the 
world's largest maker of household goods, said today the move will 
simplify its supply chain and help it cut costs by $1.4 billion 
within three years. It did not say what brands would be eliminated. 
Unilever brands include Unilever's brands include Lipton tea, 
Breyer's ice cream, Flora margarine, Wisk washing detergents, 
Calvin Klein perfumes and the Bird's Eye and Gorton's frozen foods 
lines. 

</P>
