<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Special Counsel Tours Davidian Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The special counsel investigating whether  
there was an official cover-up in the 1993 Branch Davidian siege 
has taken a personal tour of the Texas site and is asking for a 
meeting with lawyers who have filed a wrongful death lawsuit 
against the government. 
</P>
<P>
	John C. Danforth, former senator from Missouri, flew over the  
site of the sect's Mount Carmel compound outside Waco and on Monday 
walked through the ruins where cult leader David Koresh and some 80 
followers died during the standoff's fiery end on April 19, 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke with Eugene and Filomena Hipsman of Chester, N.Y., who  
were visiting the spot for the first time since their 27-year-old 
son, Peter, died in the gunfight that launched the 51-day siege. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm real sorry about the loss of your son,'' Danforth told the  
couple during his unannounced visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Danforth has written the lawyers who are  
representing surviving Davidians and relatives of the dead, asking 
for meetings with his investigators within the next two weeks. 
``The purpose of the meeting would be to obtain information from 
you on any issues relevant to my investigation,'' Danforth wrote in 
the Monday letter, obtained today by The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter requests the attorneys' views on the FBI's use of  
pyrotechnic tear gas canisters, the ``allegedly improper use of the 
U.S. armed forces,'' how certain evidence and testimony was 
presented to Congress, and who are the most important witnesses and 
evidence bearing on those issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The wrongful-death lawsuit, which accuses the government of  
using excessive force, had been set to begin next month. But U.S. 
District Judge Walter Smith in Waco last week postponed the trial's 
start to give the government more time to produce the evidence he 
has demanded. A new court date has not been set. 
</P>
<P>
	Danforth's visit to Waco and proposed meeting with the lawyers  
come on the heels of his request to Smith last week that discovery 
and depositions by plaintiffs' and government lawyers be delayed 
for a month to give him time to do his own witness questioning. 
Smith authorized the delay Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Danforth was appointed two weeks ago by Attorney General Janet  
Reno to head an independent inquiry into the actions of law 
enforcement during the deadly raid after the FBI's belated 
admission that potentially incendiary tear gas grenades were used 
in the siege's final hours. The bureau had denied the use of such 
devices for years. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials maintain that Branch Davidians, not federal  
agents, set the deadly fire. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
