<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:45:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clemency Offer 'Loser' for Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Absolutely, President Clinton said twice, for  
emphasis, when he denied that politics was involved in the clemency 
he offered 16 Puerto Rican separatists, in what Congress calls a 
deplorable concession to terrorists. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the reasoning behind his decision, it has absolutely  
not been good politics for him, or for his wife's Senate campaign 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In a five-page letter explaining his decision, Clinton said he  
did not minimize the ``serious criminal conduct'' of the people he 
granted clemency, but that their long prison sentences were out of 
proportion to their crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	In his letter to Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., on Tuesday he  
repeated that he acted on the advice of his White House counsel. 
``His recommendation and my decision were based on our view of the 
merits of the requests,'' Clinton said. ``Political considerations 
played no role in the process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional Republicans see a law-and-order issue they can  
press in House and Senate investigations, although a president's 
clemency decisions are not subject to review there. 
</P>
<P>
	No problem. Sen. Orrin Hatch, chairman of the Judiciary  
Committee and a long-shot candidate for the 2000 Republican 
presidential nomination, said he intends to look into the process, 
questioning whether the rules were followed. He also said in a Fox 
TV interview that almost anybody with brains would conclude that 
Clinton offered clemency to help Hillary Rodham Clinton in New 
York, home to about 1.3 million Puerto Ricans. And Rep. Dan Burton, 
R-Ind., said he'll show taped evidence that two of those who got 
clemency made bombs in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	If any of this actually was intended to benefit the first lady,  
it hasn't. Three weeks after Clinton's clemency offer, Mrs. Clinton 
said she was opposed to it, and that it should be withdrawn. New 
York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the likely Republican nominee for 
the Senate, had called clemency a mistake, and there was Democratic 
criticism, too. Among the Democratic opponents was Sen. Daniel 
Patrick Moynihan, whose retirement is opening the New York seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's turn against clemency angered leaders of the  
Puerto Rican political community in New York. Both Clintons said 
they had not discussed the matter before the president granted 
clemency on Aug. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen of the convicted Puerto Ricans got clemency -- freedom  
for 11, forgiven fines for three others. Two rejected Clinton's 
conditions, which included renouncing violence and avoiding 
association with people who advocate it. So it may still be an 
issue in the Senate campaign. And it could come up in the campaign 
for New York's presidential primary next March 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore has said only that he won't stand in  
judgment of Clinton's clemency decision, and has neither endorsed 
nor opposed it. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Bradley, challenging Gore for the Democratic presidential  
nomination, said he wouldn't have granted clemency. He said on ABC 
that Clinton should explain his decision to Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The House and Senate already have declared their opposition to  
clemency, by overwhelming margins. In the House, it was 311 to 41. 
The Senate vote was 95 to 2. Those are political statements, 
nothing binding because Congress has no role in clemency; the 
Constitution grants that power to presidents alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Making concessions to terrorists is deplorable,'' the  
resolutions declare, ``and ... President Clinton should not have 
granted clemency to the FALN terrorists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That is the abbreviation in Spanish for the Armed Forces of  
National Liberation, responsible for some 130 bombings and 
robberies between 1974 and 1983. Six people were killed, scores 
more injured, some of them disabled, in those episodes. Clinton's 
clemency drew protests from police and federal law enforcement 
veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the people involved ``had served very long  
sentences for offenses that did not involve bodily harm to other 
people.'' The sentences ranged from 15 to 90 years; the White House 
had called them excessive. 
</P>
<P>
	Their offenses included armed robbery, weapons violations and  
seditious conspiracy in support of FALN operations. 
</P>
<P>
	There had been pressure for years from Puerto Rican politicians,  
some in Congress, and human rights campaigners, for clemency in the 
cases of the Puerto Rican nationals. After granting it, Clinton 
pointed to the urging of figures like South African Archbishop 
Desmond Tutu and former President Carter. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Ruff conducted the final review, just before leaving his  
post as White House counsel. Clinton said it got to him in ``the 
ordinary course of business from the counsel's office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now it is part of the ordinary course of politics, Republican  
investigators versus the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
