<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 22:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Leads to Silo Gas Danger / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Persistent dry weather during the summer is  
posing a leftover danger for farmers this fall: increased risk of 
exposure to ``silo gas,'' which can burn the lungs in seconds and 
kill in minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The risk is always there. The drought just makes this year  
more serious than ever,'' Pete Gregg, spokesman for the state 
Department of Agriculture and Markets, said Tuesday. ``Farmers need 
to take heed because their lives can be in danger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the drought, most crops did not grow to full size.  
Nitrates that are usually converted to proteins for grain formation 
accumulated instead in the plants' stems, said Nate Herendeen of 
Cornell Cooperative Extension. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, corn and hay stored in a silo will ferment at a  
quicker rate and produce more nitrogen dioxide, also known as silo 
gas, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the gas is inhaled, it can dissolve the moisture in lungs  
and form nitric acid. The acid in turn burns the lungs, causing 
them to fill quickly with fluid. 
</P>
<P>
	``It literally burns, just like sulfuric acid burning. It  
displaces oxygen in the body,'' said Carol Evans, an occupational 
health nurse at the New York Center for Agricultural Medicine and 
Health. 
</P>
<P>
	Inhaling smaller concentrations over short periods of time can  
cause extensive lung damage, but inhaling large concentrations can 
mean death, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Symptoms such as coughing, shortness of breath and throat  
irritation may be immediate or could develop over a few hours or 
days after exposure. Treatment usually includes oxygen and fluid 
therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the center has investigated two silo gas inhalation  
cases in Schoharie County. One farmer was hospitalized and later 
released, Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
	Following a dry summer in 1994, the number of incidents doubled.  
Evans said the same situation is likely to happen this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is especially serious in upright silos, Herendeen  
said. Silo gas is denser than air flow down the chute and it 
gathers at the base where people and livestock may be easily 
exposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Fermentation takes three to four weeks after silos are filled.  
During that time, the area should be sealed off from the barn. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best advice is to stay away until the fermentation is  
over,'' Herendeen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans said farmers should simply be more cautious when they fork  
crops in silos. ``Sometimes it's got an odor, sometimes it doesn't. 
Sometimes you see it, sometimes you don't. It's a double whammy,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers should watch out for bleach-like odors and  
yellowish-brown fumes, which can indicate the presence of silo gas. 
</P>
<P>
	If it is really necessary to enter a silo during fermentation,  
Herendeen recommends ventilating the silo for at least 30 minutes 
with a blower. 
</P>
<P>
	Only trained professionals with self-contained breathing  
equipment should enter the silo during that time. Dust masks or 
cartridge-type respirators will not protect against silo gas, 
health officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, the state agriculture department reported  
that hay and silage corn were the crops worst-hit in New York by 
the drought. Preliminary damages were estimated at nearly $35 
million, with state officials saying the final total could go much 
higher after farmers finished harvesting all their crops. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
