<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Sept. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan Earthquake Kills 656  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's strongest quake in decades jolted  
the island early Tuesday, killing at least 656 people, wrecking a 
12-story hotel in Taipei and destroying more than 1,000 homes 
islandwide, the government said. Nearly 3,000 people were injured. 
The quake had a preliminary magnitude of 7.6 and was centered 90 
miles south-southwest of Taipei, the U.S. Geological Survey's 
National Earthquake Information Center said. It also issued 
warnings of possible tsunamis, or huge waves that sometimes follow 
earthquakes. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Addresses General Assembly  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- President Clinton can claim a broad  
international consensus on peacekeeping in Kosovo and, now, East 
Timor. But divisions over Iraq and the U.S. refusal to pay its 
debts are complicating his annual U.N. speech. Clinton will have a 
tough time persuading the international body to maintain 
decade-long sanctions on Iraq unless Baghdad agrees to allow U.N. 
weapons inspectors back into the country, U.S. officials concede. 
The president was addressing the 54th General Assembly Tuesday, and 
Iraq was a top agenda item. 

</P>
<P>
	KLA Agrees To Become Civilian Corps  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Kosovo Liberation Army, which  
has long sought to become the military of an independent Kosovo, 
has agreed with NATO-led peacekeepers to disband and be transformed 
into a civilian corps. Under the agreement reached late Monday, the 
KLA will be turned into a 5,000-member Kosovo Protection Corps, 
armed with only a handful of light weapons, under the command of 
the former rebel army's chief, Gen. Agim Ceku. Although many 
question how completely the KLA has disarmed, the deal was a 
victory for the peacekeepers, who have insisted that their force, 
known as KFOR, be the sole armed power in Kosovo, where they are 
seeking to quell ethnic violence and create a pluralist society. 

</P>
<P>
	Israeli Premier To Visit Germany  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- The symbolism is strong as Berlin, once the  
seat of Nazi power, welcomes its first state guest as the restored 
capital of Germany: Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak. By inviting 
Barak, who arrives Tuesday, Germany aims to show it is aware of the 
fears that some who suffered under the Nazis might feel now that 
the capital has returned to Berlin. Barak has warned that echoes of 
Germany's Nazi past remain amid the country's dramatic changes. 
Germany still has ``elements of extremism and neo-Nazism fermenting 
below the surface of a society in flux,'' Barak said in a recent 
interview in the German newspaper Welt Am Sonntag. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Peacekeepers Arrest Two in East Timor  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- International peacekeepers assigned to  
bring peace to East Timor arrested two people for carrying weapons 
in Dili, the capital. Australian officials said the two were 
arrested in separate incidents, one on Monday night and the other 
on Tuesday. They say one of those arrested has been linked to 
pro-Indonesian militias, while the other person is being 
questioned. The militias launched a campaign of arson, terror and 
murder, after a majority of East Timorese last month voted for 
independence from Indonesia. 

</P>
<P>
	White Supremacist Convicted in Dragging Death  
</P>
<P>
	BRYAN, Texas (AP) -- A second white supremacist was convicted  
Monday in the dragging death of a black man. Lawrence Russell 
Brewer, 32, could get the death penalty for murdering James Byrd 
Jr. in the town of Jasper last year. The jury of 11 whites and one 
Hispanic took just four hours to reach a verdict. The jury returned 
immediately to begin hearing testimony on whether Brewer should be 
sentenced to life in prison or death. Testimony in the punishment 
phase was set to continue tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	L.A. Mayor To Investigate Police Scandal  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mayor Richard Riordan promised Monday a  
thorough investigation into one of the biggest police scandals in 
city history. The mayor's involvement is the latest development in 
a 17-month police corruption investigation. At the center of the 
probe so far has been Rafael Perez, a former narcotics officer, who 
has told investigators that officers have lied in court, framed 
innocent people, and shot at least one man, then put a gun in his 
hand and arrested him for assault. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei gained 357.53 points to close at  
17,932.79. 

</P>
<P>
	Reds 12, Padres 1  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Denny Neagle pitched two-hit ball for eight  
innings and Greg Vaughn hit his 41st homer as the Cincinnati Reds 
routed the San Diego Padres 12-1 Monday night to pull within 2 1/2 
games of NL Central leader Houston. The Reds moved within 3 1/2 games 
of the idle New York Mets in the wild-card race. Houston lost to 
Pittsburgh 11-5, and the Mets were idle. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
