<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Parties Arrive in Maine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) -- Make room, Maine Democrats and  
Republicans: The Green Independent and Reform parties have arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	A state law giving the Greens and Reform parties official status  
took effect over the weekend, although it was overshadowed by a new 
smoking ban in restaurants and scores of other laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``It legitimizes the democratic process of people organizing  
into political parties,'' said Jon Carter, a veteran Green party 
activist. It also shows that the Greens ``are a strong, viable 
growing force in the political arena.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State Reform Party Chairman Wendall Kinney called the change ``a  
good move for democracy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the new law now on the books, the Green Independent and  
Reform parties will be listed along with the two major parties on 
state income tax forms' donation checkoff boxes, as well as on 
voter registration applications. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the Greens and Reform parties get to participate in  
Maine's presidential primaries on March 7, 2000, if they have 
contests, Julie Flynn, a state election official, said Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
