<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Judging Amy' Makes Strong Debut / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS is all smiles over the big audience for its  
new series, ``Judging Amy.'' Meanwhile, it's lights, camera and no 
action at Fox. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS took last week's ratings crown with television viewership  
inching up in anticipation of the new fall season, Nielsen Media 
Research said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Former ``NYPD Blue'' actress Amy Brenneman stars in ``Judging  
Amy'' as a single mother who leaves New York to become a judge in 
Hartford, Conn., living with her mother, portrayed by Tyne Daly. 
</P>
<P>
	Many critics appraised it as a knockoff of NBC's ``Providence,''  
but enough viewers tuned in to a special preview Sunday to make 
``Judging Amy'' the week's most-watched show after ``Monday Night 
Football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CBS shrewdly debuted the new series in the time slot usually  
filled by ``Touched By an Angel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's telecast of the ``Miss America'' pageant finished in 10th  
place for the week. Although its ratings were an all-time low, 
Nielsen estimated 1.3 million more people watched Saturday night's 
competition than the year before. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox's big sendoff for ``Action,'' an acclaimed comedy starring  
Jay Mohr as a noxious studio executive, fell flat. Each of the two 
new episodes that aired last Thursday had less than half the 
viewers of a ``Frasier'' rerun that NBC scheduled against it. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox's encore of the ``Action'' premiere on Sunday did even  
worse, attracting fewer viewers than professional wrestling on UPN. 
Fox finished in fourth place last week among adults aged 18-49, an 
ominous sign for a network that sees itself as young and hip. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week, CBS had an 8.0 rating and 14 share. ABC finished  
second with a 7.5 rating and 13 share, helped by football and 
``Miss America.'' NBC had a 7.0 rating and 12 share and Fox was at 
4.8 and 8. 
</P>
<P>
	The WB outpointed its mini-network rivals with a 2.6 rating and  
4 share. UPN was at 2.3 and 4 and Pax TV was at 0.8 and 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``NBC Nightly News'' won the evening news ratings race with  
a 7.6 rating and 17 share. ABC's ``World News Tonight'' had a 7.5 
rating and 16 share. Although it finished third, the ``CBS Evening 
News'' had a particularly strong week at 7.2 and 15, attributing 
its improvement largely to Dan Rather's coverage of Hurricane 
Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of Sept. 13-19, the top 10 shows, their networks  
and ratings were ``NFL Monday Night Football: Miami at Denver,'' 
ABC, 16.1; ``Judging Amy,'' CBS, 13.5; ``NFL Monday Showcase,'' 
ABC, 13.1; ``Frasier,'' NBC, 13.0; ``CBS NFL Coverage,'' CBS, 12.9; 
``60 Minutes,'' CBS, 12.4; ``Friends,'' NBC, 11.3; ``ER,'' NBC, 
10.9; ``CBS Sunday Movie: Sealed With a Kiss,'' CBS, 10.2; ``Miss 
America Pageant,'' ABC, 10.1. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
