<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brown Resurrects Gators' Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida defensive end Alex Brown  
insists he is neither a soothsayer nor a superstar. He looked like 
all that last weekend, predicting the snap count with alarming 
regularity in a five-sack performance against Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost immediately, Brown began drawing comparisons to former  
Gator Wilbur Marshall. His 14 tackles and four sacks against 
Southern California in 1982 had ranked as the best defensive 
performance in Florida history. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	Coach after coach and player after player proclaimed that  
Brown's was the best performance by a defensive player they had 
ever seen. And the compliments weren't just coming out of 
Gainesville. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brown made a couple of plays and I said, `He's going to be the  
next Superman,''' Florida State coach Bobby Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a man-child,'' said Kentucky coach Hal Mumme, who must  
devise a way to stop Brown on Saturday. ``Tennessee refused to 
block him and he took advantage of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Volunteers never kept a running back in to help block the  
6-foot-4, 251-pound sophomore. That, plus Brown's mastery of the 
Tennessee cadence, helped him blow past linemen and into Tee 
Martin's lap seemingly all night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen a guy take over a game or do as much as he did  
in one game,'' running back Earnest Graham said. ``I was amazed. It 
seemed like he was in on every play. He just played from beginning 
to end. I've never seen anything like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The performance seemed even more impressive considering the  
venom Brown spewed in the week of trash talk leading to the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We bring the house,'' Brown said in one of his more notable  
statements. ``We're going to hit him and hit him and hit him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He backed that up almost single-handedly. Brown finished with  
seven tackles, two pass deflections, a forced fumble and an 
interception. 
</P>
<P>
	Early in the first quarter, he drew a 15-yard unnecessary  
roughness penalty for knocking Martin's helmet off. It set the tone 
for a memorable night of hits. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was all just fun and games,'' Brown said of the trash  
talk. ``I try not to put too much pressure on myself. I know that I 
have to go out and give my best. And if I give my best and I only 
get one sack or I only get one tackle, I still did my best. There's 
nothing I can do about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It figures to get more difficult. Brown has eight of his team's  
16 sacks on the season, compared to 7 1/2 by last year's team leader, 
Jevon Kearse, who drew more preseason hype than most players get 
all year. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, offenses designed schemes to avoid Kearse. Could  
the same start happening for Brown? 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure people will be concerned about him because he made  
big plays,'' defensive coordinator Jon Hoke said. ``If I was an 
offensive person, I'd be a little concerned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown arrived at Florida after being named Most Valuable Player  
in his district on both defense, as a linebacker, and offense, as a 
quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew he was good from day one,'' receiver Alex Willis said.  
``A guy that big playing quarterback the way he did -- you know he's 
an athlete. You know he can make plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now everybody else does, too.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
