<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Sink; Dow Closes Down 225.43 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply Tuesday, driving the Dow  
Jones industrials down 225 points, as traders grew uneasy about the 
weakening dollar, the growing U.S. trade deficit and upcoming 
earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow fell 225.43 to 10,598.47 after falling as much as 272.03  
during the session. The index's decline, which amounted to 2 
percent, was its biggest one-day point drop since it fell 235.53 on 
May 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also dropped sharply. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index fell 27.95 to 1,307.57, and the Nasdaq composite 
index fell 65.05 to 2,821.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the market's big losses, analysts said the selloff was a  
calm one, mostly growing out of the uncertainties raised by recent 
economic news. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no panic selling,'' said Barry Berman, head trader for  
Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co. in Milwaukee. ``It has the feel of a market 
that was a little overextended, given the background of 
uncertainty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tiremaker Goodyear and computer maker Hewlett Packard were the  
biggest losers among the Dow stocks. Goodyear, which reportedly 
expected third-quarter earnings to be disappointing, fell 4 5/8 to 47 
5/16. Hewlett Packard slipped 4 11/16 to 99 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Foremost in many investors' minds was the dollar's continuing  
slide against the Japanese yen. The U.S. currency was quoted at 
about 105 yen Tuesday, down from 106 yen on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	A weaker dollar can be inflationary and lead to higher interest  
rates in this country. The rising yen also attracts investors to 
Asian markets and away from U.S. stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	In this economic climate, investors increasingly worry that the  
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates for a third time this 
year to combat inflation, a move that would raise borrowing costs 
and erode corporate profits. The Fed's policy-setting Open Market 
Committee meets in two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fear of another interest rate hike is clearly weighing  
heavily on the market for now,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment 
officer at BankBoston. He said that anxiety was keeping stocks 
trading within a specific range -- with the Dow shuttling between 
10,500 and 11,300. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Riley noted that although September is a historically  
bearish month for the market, stocks aren't far from their highs 
for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Early morning news that the trade deficit ballooned to a monthly  
record of $25.2 billion in July disappointed investors. To many 
economists' surprise, imports rose to an all-time high as consumers 
bought foreign cars and other overseas goods. 
</P>
<P>
	With earnings reports for the current quarter expected within  
the next few weeks, the market was extremely sensitive to any bad 
news about profits. So prices also tumbled in response to Apple 
Computer's announcement late Monday that its earnings for this 
quarter would be hurt by a shortage of chips. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple's shortage was unrelated to the earthquake in Taiwan,  
where many computer chips are made. But the announcement 
disappointed market watchers who had been expecting improved 
profits. The computer maker fell 9 13/16 to 69 1/4, while Motorola -- 
Apple's supplier -- fell 2 13/16 to 87 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taiwan earthquake, meanwhile, led a range of other  
semiconductor stocks to fall. Applied Materials fell 2 1/2 to 81 5/16, 
while Texas Instruments fell 1 5/8 to 86 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-3 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, with 697 up, 2,362 down and 492 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 970.43 million shares, vs. 698.92 million in  
the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies dropped 6.70 to  
426.50. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.03 percent.  
Germany's DAX index closed down 1.29 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 
fell 1.64 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 1.44 percent. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
