<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Author Accused of Plagiarism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Scottish author accused of plagiarism four  
times before has had his biography of U.S. naval hero John Paul 
Jones put on hold by the publisher, The New York Times reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I Have Not Yet Begun to Fight: A Life of John Paul Jones'' by  
James Mackay was due for October release by the Atlantic Monthly 
Press of Grove/Atlantic Inc. It is a full-length biography of the 
Scottish-born Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	But the publisher has halted publication to check similarities  
to the last major Jones biography, published in 1959 by the late 
Samuel Eliot Morison, the Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am holding back distribution and getting an independent  
evaluation,'' Grove/Atlantic president and publisher Morgan 
Entrekin said. About 7,500 freshly printed copies of Mackay's $28 
book have been put on hold. 
</P>
<P>
	Mackay, who has written more than 100 books, denied copying  
Morison's ``John Paul Jones: A Sailor's Biography.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the two biographies share similar passages in part  
because ``there are only a certain number of words in the English 
language.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Entrekin acknowledged that before last week he had never talked  
to Mackay (pronounced muhk-EYE) or asked questions about past 
plagiarism allegations. Scholars and other authors have accused 
Mackay of plagiarizing material for four other books since 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, another publisher recalled and destroyed thousands  
of copies of a Mackay book because of copyright infringement 
issues. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0156 </DOCNO>
