<DOCNO> APW19990921.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 17:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Temporary Homes Coming to N.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TARBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Villages of trailer homes and campers  
sprung up Tuesday for 1,000 families whose homes were swallowed by 
the floodwaters of Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	It will still be a few days before the temporary homes open, and  
many weary evacuees welcomed the chance to get out of shelters. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll be a home. I can call that a home because there's nobody  
but me and my family in one camper,'' said Angela Davis, who has 
been staying with her son, daughter and hundreds of others at 
Tarboro High School. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Floyd dumped 20 inches of rain on eastern North  
Carolina on Thursday with catastrophic effect: 40 confirmed deaths, 
30,000 flooded homes, 10,000 people in shelters. 
</P>
<P>
	About 47,000 people remained without power and nearly 300 roads  
remained closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Altogether, the storm caused at least 68 deaths from the Bahamas  
to New England. In New Jersey, more than a million did not have 
safe water to drink. 
</P>
<P>
	The early damage estimate of $1.3 billion is expected to soar  
and may well exceed the $6 billion for Hurricane Fran in 1996, the 
state's costliest natural disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jim Hunt asked people to pitch in with efforts to rebuild  
homes and repair the damage to the state's economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a long and difficult job restoring people and their  
communities to their normal lives,'' Hunt said in a speech 
broadcast statewide. ``But we can do it, we will do it, and we 
won't quit until the job is finished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By air and by boat, rescue workers continued to look for anyone  
still stranded in flooded areas Tuesday night, but the state was 
unsure how many people that might be. 
</P>
<P>
	At Tarboro High, home to an estimated 1,500 to 2,000 evacuees,  
people were sleeping on cots in classrooms and the gymnasium. The 
school had no running water. People bathed in shower tents hooked 
up to water tankers. Portable toilets were overflowing. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have right now is like a small city,'' said Dave Stone  
of the American Red Cross, the shelter's manager. ``It would be 
nice to have flushable toilets, but that's not in the foreseeable 
future. Thank God we've got power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many people also were without their cars.  
</P>
<P>
	AAA Carolinas motor club estimated that as many as 40,000 to  
50,000 vehicles were damaged by the flooding, many belonging to 
low-income residents without adequate insurance to replace them. 
</P>
<P>
	Agricultural damage was devastating. At least 2.9 million  
poultry and 100,000 hogs drowned. Sewage plants and hog waste 
lagoons were swamped by the fast, brown waters. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffins, bloated animal carcasses and household goods could be  
seen bobbing in the polluted floodwaters across an 
18,000-square-mile area. 
</P>
<P>
	Two inches of rain fell Tuesday, delaying efforts to fire up  
incinerators and begin destroying the carcasses to prevent the 
spread of disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers also were coping with how to save livestock that  
survived the floodwaters but lacked food and shelter. Drivers were 
trying to get feed to farms, though it took two to three times as 
long as normal to make deliveries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to take a real circuitous route to get to them,'' said  
John Pike, director of operations at Goldsboro Milling Co. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
