<DOCNO> APW19990921.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Planning New Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo Stock Exchange plans a new stock market  
for emerging companies that will relax conventional listing 
requirements, exchange president Mitsuhide Yamaguchi said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The market, set to open in November, will be nicknamed  
``Mothers,'' for ``market of the high-growth and emerging stocks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It will have no profit-history criteria for listing and will  
only require sales figures as evidence of existing business 
operations, Yamaguchi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mothers will target ventures whose core operations are in  
emerging industries or are based on new technology, Yamaguchi said. 
Many will probably be computer or biotechnology related. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies will have to report earnings results every quarter,  
Yamaguchi said. Other firms on the Tokyo exchange must report 
results twice a year. 
</P>
<P>
	All Mothers companies to have a market capitalization of $4.7  
million through an initial public offering of at least 1,000 
shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Listed companies also have to create 300 new shareholders  
through the initial public offering, Yamaguchi said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 40 companies have already shown an interest in applying  
for listing on the new market, Yamaguchi said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We named the market MOTHERS with hope that it will help the  
growth of emerging companies in a motherly way,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
