<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Executes Dying Killer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- A convicted killer who dropped his  
appeals so he would be executed before dying of hepatitis C was put 
to death by injection Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Wayne Smith, 43, killed a Houston special education  
teacher who was moonlighting as a convenience store clerk in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith decided last year to drop his appeals so he wouldn't die  
from his advancing hepatitis C. His liver was failing and he used a 
wheelchair. 
</P>
<P>
	When a warden asked Smith whether he had a final statement, he  
said, ``No, sir.'' With a tear glistening under his right eye, 
Smith licked his lips, closed his eyes and exhaled twice before 
dying. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith was the 25th person executed in Texas this year and the  
fourth this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Smith robbed a convenience store where Karen  
Birky, 38, worked so she could buy supplies for her special 
education students. Ms. Birky complied with Smith's demand for 
money before he walked her into the parking lot, shot her in the 
neck and fled. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith is thought to have contracted hepatitis through a shared  
heroin needle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
