<HEADLINE> Clinton Bothered by Hoarseness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- President Clinton continued to struggle  
with hoarseness today, nearly a week after straining his voice 
during his trip to New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	The president's voice broke at least twice today as he addressed  
the United Nations General Assembly. He cleared his throat each 
time, freeing up enough vocal power to finish his speech. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, who has suffered periodic bouts of hoarseness  
throughout his presidency, said last week that he strained his 
voice during the 20-hour return flight from New Zealand, where he 
participated in an economic summit with Asia-Pacific leaders. He 
spent a lot of time talking during that flight, making calls to 
governors and federal officials dealing with Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton did not have any voice problems during his visit Monday  
to hurricane-damaged sections of North Carolina. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
