<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Agent Testifies at Bank Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A scenario used by former CIA Director R. James Woolsey to  
illustrate the close connections between Russian business, 
organized crime groups and intelligence and law enforcement 
agencies. Woolsey was testifying Tuesday at a House Banking 
Committee hearing on an alleged huge money-laundering scheme 
involving the Russian mob and the Bank of New York: 
</P>
<P>
	``If you should chance to strike up a conversation with an  
articulate, English-speaking Russian in, say, the restaurant of one 
of the luxury hotels along Lake Geneva (Switzerland), and he is 
wearing a $3,000 suit and a pair of Gucci loafers, and he tells you 
that he is an executive of a Russian trading company and wants to 
talk to you about a joint venture, then there are four 
possibilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``He may be what he says he is. He may be a Russian intelligence  
officer working under commercial cover. He may be part of a Russian 
organized crime group. But the really interesting possibility is 
that he may be all three -- and that none of those three 
institutions have any problem with the arrangement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woolsey also said corruption and organized crime in Russia is  
one of the most important issues the United States faces because: 
</P>
<P>
	--They have the potential to destabilize the Russian state, which  
has a nuclear arsenal. 
</P>
<P>
	--There is a real possibility that Russian organized crime groups  
may be, or become, involved in the sale of technology or materials 
for weapons of mass destruction or other modern military 
technology. 
</P>
<P>
	--Russian organized crime can use its resources to corrupt  
institutions in the United States. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
