<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Send Relief Adviser to NY, NJ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- President Clinton dispatched his top  
disaster-relief adviser to flood-stricken New Jersey and New York 
today to make sure that federal assistance after Hurricane Floyd is 
being delivered ``responsibly, efficiently and in adequate 
amounts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A day after inspecting damage in North Carolina, Clinton said,  
``I know people in New Jersey and New York have also been 
injured.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president spoke at the Wall Street helipad on his arrival in  
New York to address the United Nations General Assembly. He said 
that James Lee Witt, director of the Federal Emergency Management 
Agency, would visit New York and New Jersey to inspect the damage 
and ``report back immediately on what more we need to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president has issued disaster declarations for both states  
to speed federal relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing all we can at the federal level,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I want to make sure that the assistance is delivered  
responsibly, efficiently and in adequate amounts,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In difficult times like this, we're reminded that the power of  
the American spirit is even stronger than the power of a hurricane. 
The American people are supporting all those who have been injured 
in this and we will stand by them until they recover.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Clinton declared a major disaster in Delaware and ordered  
federal aid to boost state and local recovery efforts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
