<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rain spread across wide areas of the East on Tuesday as a cold  
front moved through the region and Tropical Storm Harvey soaked 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvey was poorly organized but poured more than 10 inches of  
rain across southern Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm, born in the Gulf of Mexico, initially was forecast to  
cross central Florida, but it turned southward early Tuesday and 
was expected to cross the southern tip of Florida and the Bahamas 
on its way out into the Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind gusted to 53 mph and trees were reported blown down in  
Everglades National Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The cold front curved from the lower Mississippi Valley across  
the Tennessee Valley and Appalachians into New England. 
</P>
<P>
	During the afternoon, showers and occasional thunderstorms were  
scattered along the front from Mississippi across Tennessee, 
Kentucky, southern Ohio, West Virginia, Pennsylvania, New York, 
Massachusetts, Vermont, New Hampshire and Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	A band of showers and a few thunderstorms also stretched along  
the East Coast, with heavy rainfall along the North Carolina shore 
and from Washington to Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, scattered showers developed during the afternoon from  
southern California across southern sections of Arizona and New 
Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a  
morning low of 23 at West Yellowstone, Mont., to a midday reading 
of 85 at Yuma, Ariz., and Palm Springs, Calif. The lowest wind 
chill was 16 at Leadville, Colo., and the highest heat index by the 
middle of the day was 94 at Marathon, Fla. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
