<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Athletic Dir. Bockrath Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- Alabama athletic director Bob Bockrath  
resigned Tuesday, ending a rocky three-year term with the school. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama president Andrew Sorensen praised Bockrath for  
developing the school's facilities and for following NCAA rules, 
but said ``from an administrative and leadership standpoint, a 
change was needed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finus Gaston, Alabama's senior associate AD, will fill in on an  
interim basis. A national search will be launched to find a 
permanent replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	Sorensen said Bockrath would be assigned other duties until June  
30, 2000. He is expected to take sick leave during part of the time 
to recover from shoulder surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that Bockrath is out, the focus turns to football coach Mike  
DuBose's future. 
</P>
<P>
	Bockrath, who hired DuBose, chose to punish the coach rather  
than fire him when he admitted lying about a relationship with a 
university employee. The school settled a sexual harassment 
complaint filed by the woman in August and Bockrath cut two years 
off DuBose's contract. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose, whose team lost 29-28 to Louisiana Tech on Saturday,  
said Monday he has heard the calls by some for his job. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I don't worry about it,'' DuBose said. ``I can't worry  
about it, I can't linger on it. I come to work every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose said he didn't know whether his position was further  
weakened by Bockrath's departure. DuBose, who has a 13-13 career 
record at Alabama, said Monday that he hadn't considered resigning. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love this university and if I was 100 percent convinced it  
was the best thing for this university, sure, I would consider 
it,'' he said. ``But I have not considered it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bockrath's departure came just days after university trustees  
formed a committee to oversee athletics in the three-campus Alabama 
system. While trustees said the panel had no direct control, some 
saw the move as stripping Bockrath of his power. 
</P>
<P>
	Bockrath came to Alabama from Texas Tech in June 1996. Within  
six months, Gene Stallings had resigned as football coach and 
Bockrath, following what the fans and alumni were calling for, 
hired DuBose as his replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	An Ohio native who never played for or coached with former  
Alabama coach Bear Bryant, Bockrath was viewed as an outsider by 
most fans. 
</P>
<P>
	He gained support for the big things -- like hiring the popular  
choices to coach the Crimson Tide's football and basketball teams 
and for moving SEC football games out of Legion Field in 
Birmingham. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Bockrath was vilified for little things -- like  
changing the brand of soft drinks sold at Alabama events and for 
not securing enough tickets to last year's Music City Bowl. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
