<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 15:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Radical Student To Be Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Katherine Ann Power, the '60s radical who went  
underground for two decades after the slaying of a police officer, 
gets out of prison next week after serving six years of an eight- 
to 12-year sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	For the family of Officer Walter Schroeder, who was gunned down  
on Sept. 22, 1970 -- 29 years ago this week -- while trying to 
prevent a bank robbery, that hardly seems like enough time. But 
there's not much they can do about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think six years is a fairly light sentence when you're  
talking about circumstances involving the death of somebody,'' said 
Clare Schroeder, one of Schroeder's nine children, and one of 
several who became police officers. But she added: ``It's a fait 
accompli. She's done the maximum amount of time under the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Power, then a 20-year-old Brandeis University student, was  
waiting in a getaway car during the robbery, which was intended to 
fund the movement against the Vietnam War. The heist, which netted 
$26,000, went awry when William ``Lefty'' Gilday shot Schroeder in 
the back with a submachine gun. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilday was captured days later and was convicted of murder and  
sentenced to life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Power fled. She took the alias Alice Metzinger, lived in women's  
communes, gave birth to a son and settled near Corvallis, Ore., 
where she married a bookkeeper, Ronley Duncan, and became known for 
her cooking at a tea and coffee house. 
</P>
<P>
	Although she shared her secret with Duncan, her past ate away at  
her. She hadn't seen her parents since college. After beginning 
therapy for depression, she decided to have a lawyer negotiate for 
her surrender. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, or 23 years after she went underground, Power returned  
to Massachusetts and pleaded guilty to manslaughter. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, during a parole hearing, she apologized to the  
Schroeder family and dropped her bid for early release. 
</P>
<P>
	With time off for good behavior, she will get out on Oct. 2.  
</P>
<P>
	At the Boston Police Department, whose headquarters building is  
dedicated to Schroeder and his brother, another officer killed in 
the line of duty, officials said it was difficult accepting Power's 
relatively short sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the feelings of the Boston Police Department are she  
didn't serve enough time for what she took from the family and from 
the city,'' said a police spokeswoman, Sgt. Detective Margot Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	Under her plea agreement, Power is barred from selling her  
story. She has denied requests for interviews, saying the media 
have focused too much on her and not enough on the Schroeders. 
</P>
<P>
	During Power's time in prison, several people who knew her in  
Oregon wrote the parole board in support of her, including some 
restaurateurs who promised to hire her once she was released. Her 
lawyer, James M. Doyle, said he is not sure what she plans to do 
after she is released. 
</P>
<P>
	Reached at his Oregon home Tuesday morning, Duncan said he did  
not know his wife was about to be released. He declined further 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Power's release comes as another radical who spent years as a  
fugitive, Kathleen Ann Soliah, awaits trial on charges that she 
planted bombs under Los Angeles police cars in 1975. She was 
arrested in June in St. Paul, Minn., where she had settled into a 
comfortable life as Sara Jane Olson, an actress, a doctor's wife 
and a mother of three. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
