<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley's Plan for Campaign Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Bill Bradley, expanding on his campaign  
finance reform proposal, suggested Tuesday that special interest 
groups that run political advertisements should pay for their 
opponents to respond. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic presidential candidate said he also supports  
public financing of general elections, free television time for 
candidates 60 days before an election and a ban on unregulated 
contributions to political parties, known as ``soft money''. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that if a special interest group wants to run political  
ads, opposing groups should be given free air time so voters will 
hear more than one voice. Or, the interest group that wants to air 
an ad should have to pay for a response by its opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the way to deal with that is to say if you're going to  
buy issue ads, there's got to be equal time for the other side,'' 
he said on New Hampshire Public Radio's ``The Exchange''. ``Or when 
issue ads are on, a 100 percent tax is given to the other side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few minutes later, a caller said he was appalled by the idea.  
</P>
<P>
	``You are compelling people to support the opposing view,'' said  
a man named Robin from Hanover. ``And you assume there is an 
opposing view, rather than many opposing views.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, a former New Jersey senator, said the caller made a  
good point but defended the plan as ``simply a way to allow the 
market to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reacting quickly, Republican National Committee Chairman Jim  
Nicholson called Bradley's proposal ``the silliest notion we've 
heard this campaign season. Essentially, what Bradley is proposing 
is a new speech tax.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley also said he plans to announce a major health care  
reform plan in the next two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a major effort to cover as many Americans as  
possible,'' he said. ``The issue here is can you do this in a way 
that preserves quality, puts doctors back in charge of 
decision-making, covers a lot more people than now and does so at a 
cost that you can put before the people?'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to answer a question about whether the plan is based  
on the current private insurance system. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you pull the string in one place with that question, it  
leads to 50 other things,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent polls in New Hampshire and New York have shown a tight  
race between Bradley and his only Democratic presidential opponent, 
Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had no expectations about when things would move or when  
they wouldn't,'' Bradley said at a rally at his Manchester 
headquarters. ``Someone came up to me and said, `We have momentum.' 
I said, `No we don't, we have a little traction.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
