<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Union, Ford Canada Talks Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The Canadian Auto Workers union said Tuesday that  
negotiations for a new contract with Ford Motor Co. were going 
well, but that there was still a chance that workers would go on 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very close to an agreement,'' CAW President Buzz  
Hargrove said Tuesday afternoon. ``I'd say we are slightly over 90 
percent ... But there are still issues here that would cause a 
national strike with Ford.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three-year contract between the union and Ford that covers  
13,000 workers expires at midnight Tuesday. As a rule, the union 
does not extend its contracts while negotiations are underway. The 
CAW held a three-week strike against General Motors Corp. during 
the last round of negotiations in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	A strike at Ford plants in Canada could disrupt the supply of  
engines for some of Ford's most profitable vehicles, including 
large F-series pickups and the Lincoln Navigator and Ford 
Expedition sport utility vehicles. Ford also assembles its Windstar 
minivan and Ford Crown Victoria and Mercury Grand Marquis sedans in 
Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks continued Tuesday at a Toronto hotel.  
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove said one of the major sticking points was the union's  
demands on work contracted out to suppliers. The CAW has asked Ford 
to tell non-unionized suppliers not to interfere in union drives; 
as automakers have shifted work to parts suppliers, the CAW has 
sought to organize supplier plants. 
</P>
<P>
	If the CAW was able to get such an agreement from Ford, it would  
expect a similar agreement from GM and DaimlerChrysler AG. A 
neutrality promise on plant organizing was reportedly part of a 
tenative agreement reached Thursday between DaimlerChrysler AG and 
the United Auto Workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove did say the union and Ford had resolved wage and  
pension issues. While not giving any details, Hargrove said the 
pension agreement was ``light years'' ahead of a Ford proposal he 
criticized Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove had criticized Ford's first wage proposal, including a  
1 percent raise in each year of a three-year contract and a signing 
bonus of $500 for each worker, as shocking. 
</P>
<P>
	The average Canadian line worker at Ford earns a base wage of  
about $16 U.S. dollars an hour, while skilled workers earn $19 at 
current conversion rates. Similar workers in the United States earn 
$20.71 and $24.38 an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	During the last round of bargaining with automakers, the union  
won wage increases of two per cent in each year of a three-year 
deal. The UAW's tentative deal with DaimlerChrysler calls for a 3 
percent raise in each year of a four-year deal, plus a $1,350 
signing bonus. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
