<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 00:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> States May Lose Funds Over Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- White House drug control director Barry  
McCaffrey says Congress should rethink penalties in an anti-smoking 
law that have jeopardized $37 million in drug treatment dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has notified seven states and the District of  
Columbia that because they haven't sufficiently curtailed underage 
smoking, the law requires 40 percent cuts in 1999 block grants for 
substance abuse and treatment programs. 
</P>
<P>
	States that failed to meet target rates for reducing sales of  
tobacco products to minors may appeal the ruling, and if they fail, 
states can choose to pay the penalty from this year's budget or 
have the funds shaved from the budget for fiscal 2000, which begins 
Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	White House drug control director Barry McCaffrey criticized the  
law as too harsh because he said it may force some drug treatment 
centers to close and ``some heroin addicts might be forced back on 
the streets to return to a criminal life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Named for the late Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., the 1992 law  
requires states to pass laws banning tobacco sales to anyone under 
age 18 and aggressively enforce those laws through random, 
unannounced inspections and other measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri merchants were supposed to be found to selling tobacco  
to minors fewer than 28 percent of the time last year under random 
checks using decoys at grocers and other retailers. But the state's 
failure rate was 33 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress passed a law and it is our job to enforce that law,''  
said Mark Weber, spokesman for the Substance Abuse and Mental 
Health Services Administration. ``This program has had tremendous 
success in reducing youth access to tobacco.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inspection failures have dropped to 25 percent from a rate of 40  
percent in 1997, Weber said. The rate was at least 60 percent when 
the regulations took effect, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'll find that everyone is in favor of the goals and what  
the law has accomplished,'' Weber said. ``What you're finding 
disagreement with is the harshness of the penalty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri stands to lose the most, $9.6 million. Cuts could limit  
services from treatment for pregnant crack addicts to housing for 
addicted kids, said Michael Couty, director of the alcohol and drug 
abuse division of the Missouri Department of Mental Health. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the area of prevention, it would limit the amount of  
dollars available to work with communities to deal with issues of 
selling tobacco to minors, which gets right at the heart of the 
issue,'' Couty said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials in Missouri originally set a 1999 target rate using  
methodology that was recently changed to be more strict, and they 
blamed poor enforcement on inaccurate reporting by local law 
officers whose attention is consumed by an explosion in 
methamphetamine manufacturing. 
</P>
<P>
	The other states were Delaware, with a $2.2 million penalty;  
Iowa, $5 million; Minnesota, $8.4 million; Oregon, $6 million; 
Rhode Island, $2.4 million; and Wyoming, $980,950. The District of 
Columbia would lose nearly $2 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 05:40:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flight Attendants Boot Negotiators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Flight attendants who have rejected a proposed  
contract with American Airlines have also tossed out their 
negotiating committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Association of Professional Flight Attendants on Monday  
created an advisory panel to guide the next round of negotiations 
with the nation's No. 2 carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the union representing 21,000 flight attendants at  
American, said that members had voted down the contract by a 
2 1/2-to-1 ratio. 
</P>
<P>
	The union, in a recorded message left on a hot line for members,  
said its president, Denise Hedges, ``will no longer serve as 
spokesperson for the next APFA negotiating committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hedges, who had served as negotiating committee chairwoman,  
strongly supported the tentative agreement, which was rejected by 
73.2 percent of the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not unusual for airline contracts to be rejected on the  
first attempt,'' said Ms. Hedges. ``The fact that this tendency was 
repeated on this very strong contract is a clear indication that 
flight attendants want more from their jobs. That is something that 
all airlines, not just American, have to come to grips with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal would have included pay raises totaling 15.9  
percent between November 1999 and November 2003. Also in the 
package was a 3 percent signing bonus, extra pay for workers with 
25 years of experience and additional employer contributions to 
workers' 401(k) plans. 
</P>
<P>
	However, opponents said the proposal's annual pay raises were  
too small and profit-sharing would have been eliminated. Also, 
attendants would have worked more hours each month under the 
proposal that required payment in advance for medical coverage in 
retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	The APFA board of directors bypassed their national elected  
leadership to create the five-person advisory committee, which 
includes two former association presidents, Patt Gibbs and Tommie 
Hutto-Blake. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee members discussed the failed vote and a new round of  
negotiations Monday afternoon with the airline's negotiating 
committee, headed by Sue Oliver, vice president of employee 
relations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have tremendous respect for the APFA negotiating committee,  
whose dedication and very hard work resulted in a tentative 
agreement last May, and we wish them well as they return to 
flying,'' American spokeswoman Karen Watson said. ``However, we 
will continue to work with whatever negotiating committee the APFA 
assembles.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 22:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Big Dairy Cos. Consolidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Suiza Foods Corp. solidified its standing as the  
nation's leading milk processor by acquiring Southern Foods Group, 
which has a stable of well-known brands in the South Central 
states. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company would have annual sales of $6 billion and  
distribute such well-known regional dairy brands as Borden, Elsie 
and Meadow Gold in 46 states. 
</P>
<P>
	``This clearly establishes Suiza as the leader of the fluid-milk  
market, with about a 20 percent market share,'' said analyst 
Romitha Mally of Goldman Sachs. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition announced Tuesday makes Suiza a national player  
and therefore more attractive to large supermarket chains that want 
to buy goods from suppliers with broad reach, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza is strongest in the Southeast and Southern California, and  
chairman Gregg Engles said the acquisition of Southern will extend 
the company's geographic reach. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were one of the few big independent producers that we had  
an opportunity to do something with,'' he said. ``It really makes 
us a national dairy company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza was founded in 1993 as a holding company for acquiring  
food and dairy processors and has grown rapidly through 
acquisitions, especially in the Southeast and Southern California, 
to 56 processing plants and 12,400 employees. It has made more than 
30 acquisitions in the past three years, and produces packaged food 
and ice in addition to dairy goods. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza's main rival, Dean Foods Co. of Franklin Park, Ill., with  
fiscal 1999 sales of nearly $3.8 billion, has also been acquiring 
smaller operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza and Southern, both based in Dallas, will form a joint  
venture to include all domestic milk processing activities of both 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza will own 66.2 percent of the venture, to be called the  
Suiza Fluid Dairy Group, with Southern's partner, Dairy Farmers of 
America Inc., owning the other 33.8 percent. The two recently 
launched similar joint ventures in Southern California and several 
Northeast states. 
</P>
<P>
	No cash will change hands in the deal, said Engles, but each  
company will contribute its assets to the joint venture. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Suiza had revenue of $3.3 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Southern, with revenue of nearly $1.2 billion in 1998, has 25  
plants and 5,100 employees. It is concentrated in Texas and 
Oklahoma but serves other markets, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Counting the full-year revenues of operations that Suiza has  
acquired during the past year, the revenue of the combined company 
for the 12 months ended June 30 would be about $6 billion, said 
Suiza's chief financial officer, Barry Fromberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza also announced that its president and chief operating  
officer, G. Irwin Gordon, is leaving the company to pursue other, 
unspecified interests. His duties will be divided among several 
executives at different divisions, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Directors of both companies have unanimously approved the  
transaction, which faces a federal antitrust review. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 15:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals' Moore Signs $17.5M Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Wide receiver Rob Moore signed a four-year, $17.5  
million contract with the Arizona Cardinals on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, 31, will receive a $5 million signing bonus as part of  
the deal. This year, including the bonus and salary, he gets $8 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The signing means the Cardinals can remove the franchise player  
designation from Moore and use it on another player, such as 
defensive end Simeon Rice, whose contract expires after this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore held out throughout training camp, but reported to the  
team three days before its Sept. 12 season opener at Philadelphia, 
then caught a 20-yard touchdown pass from Jake Plummer in that 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	At that time, he agreed to a one-year deal worth about $3.5  
million with the understanding that his agent, Gary Wichard, and 
the Cardinals would continue to work on a long-term contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``The big thing was Rob didn't want anything to interfere with  
this season,'' Wichard said. ``He said, `Gary, the difference 
between 9-7 and 8-8 could be the playoffs.' We were close, so he 
said, `Let me get in there and play while you guys finish out your 
deal.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, in his 10th NFL season, is 20th on the career receiving  
list with 596 catches for 8,872 yards and 45 touchdowns. Two years 
ago, he led the NFL in yards receiving with a Cardinals record 
1,584. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore is nursing a strained hamstring this week, an injury from  
the final play of Sunday's 19-16 loss to Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	He is so crucial to Arizona's offense that quarterback Jake  
Plummer uncharacteristically chastised management for failing to 
sign the big-play receiver. Three days later, Moore was with the 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, Frank Sanders and rookie David Boston give the Cardinals  
a dynamic trio of receivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is, Rob takes attention away from Frank, and he's  
also a great asset to the new kid,'' Wichard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two players remain locked in a contract dispute with the  
Cardinals: defensive tackle Mark Smith and rookie offensive tackle 
L.J. Shelton. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's agent, Gil Thompson, has said his client would report at  
some point. Thompson has lowered Smith's demand to about $700,000, 
but the Cardinals had withdrawn their $500,000 proposal and had 
gone back to their original $325,000 tender offer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
