<DOCNO> APW19990921.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 08:13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Peacekeepers Move Into East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Tanks, trucks and armored personnel  
carriers rumbled off warships in Dili today as international forces 
took control of East Timor. Jubilant citizens cheered the 
peacekeepers and mocked the demoralized Indonesian troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian soldiers took over warehouses pillaged by militia  
gangs and their Indonesian army backers, while other troops 
arrested gang members and stripped them of machetes and homemade 
guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the early optimism, force commander Maj. Gen. Peter  
Cosgrove cautioned that East Timor will not be under full control 
for some weeks and will remain dangerous until then. He said his 
troops will begin moving outside the capital on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will still be a number of weeks rather than days before we  
are in a position to have a pervasive presence in the province,'' 
Cosgrove said. ``It is too early for us to assert that the security 
situation overall is anything approaching benign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Dili, hundreds of refugees streamed out of the hills where  
they had sought refuge, returning to watch the U.N.-mandated force, 
which began arriving Monday, take control of the burned-out capital 
after the militias' three-week campaign of terror. As an Australian 
navy catamaran pulled into port, some broke into a traditional East 
Timorese dance of welcome. 
</P>
<P>
	With 24 years of iron-fisted Indonesian rule ending, Indonesian  
President B.J. Habibie urged lawmakers in Jakarta today to accept 
East Timor's overwhelming vote for independence in an Aug. 30 
referendum. He said acceptance would help restore Indonesia's 
international image. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Indonesia's highest legislative body still must  
approve the independence vote in a session expected by November. 
Opponents have said the presence of international peacekeepers 
violates national sovereignty. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have done the best I could,'' Habibie said. ``I have been  
able to prevent Balkanization,'' he added, referring to fears that 
Indonesia could follow Yugoslavia on a path to violent 
disintegration. 
</P>
<P>
	The referendum results sparked a rampage by militiamen, who  
drove out hundreds of thousands of civilians, killed independence 
supporters, burned homes and looted, abetted by Indonesian troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Human rights workers and refugees say hundreds, perhaps  
thousands of people, were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Defense Minister Gen. Wiranto said the figure was far  
smaller. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were only 90 victims, not, as outsiders said, thousands  
dead,'' told parliament on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dare, site of a large refugee camp six miles south of Dili,  
people burst into tears of joy as international soldiers in full 
battle gear and a group of United Nations officials drove up in a 
convoy of U.N. vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Viva Timor Leste,'' chanted the crowd, or ``Long live East  
Timor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Between 190,000 to 300,000 people fled into hiding in the  
mountains and other areas during the violence, in addition to 
141,000 who fled to Indonesian-controlled West Timor, according to 
a report by the U.N. Children's Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian troops used landing craft to unload trucks, jeeps,  
bulldozers and other heavy equipment from landing craft. Warehouses 
were being stocked with food, medicine and other supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Several truckloads of independence supporters drove past the  
dwindling number of Indonesian soldiers, jeering and making abusive 
gestures. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are delighted with the U.N. troops. This is the final  
defeat of the Indonesian military in East Timor,'' said Filomena 
Bianco, 34.''Indonesia will have to pay reparations for the loss of 
our hometown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Multinational troops stepped up the pressure on remaining gang  
members in and around Dili. Soldiers manning a roadblock near Dili 
airport halted a taxi with six men and discovered several weapons. 
The men were handcuffed and led away for further questioning. 
</P>
<P>
	Two others were arrested for carrying weapons in Dili in two  
separate incidents this morning and the night before, said Maj. 
George O'Kane. One of the men was carrying documents linking him 
with a militia group, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many militiamen have fled ahead of the peacekeepers' deployment,  
and an Australian military spokesman, Col. Duncan Lewis, said there 
had been ``very little militia action'' since peacekeepers arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	Chaos reigned at the Indonesian military headquarters as  
soldiers loaded up furniture and filing cabinets. Most Indonesian 
troops are due to leave in the next several days, leaving behind a 
token force that has been ordered to cooperate with the 
peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to go home. I'm tired of this place,'' said an  
Indonesian soldier who refused to give his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the troops in East Timor today were from Australia.  
Others came from Britain, France, New Zealand, the Philippines, 
Thailand and the United States. The U.S. non-combat contingent has 
sent in small reconnaissance teams so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen other countries have pledged personnel or indicated a  
willingness to contribute. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia invaded East Timor in 1975 after Portugal left the  
colony it held for 400 years. More than 3,700 Indonesian troops 
died in the first five years, fighting a determined resistance 
movement. 
</P>
<P>
	East Timor's independence leader, Jose Alexandre ``Xanana''  
Gusmao said in Darwin, Australia, that he would return to his 
homeland soon. In his first comments since international forces 
moved in, Gusmao thanked international leaders and their forces for 
intervening to stop the bloodshed by anti-independence forces. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990921.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 08:13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
