<HEADLINE> Alcohol Control Board Leader Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The director of New Jersey's Alcoholic  
Beverage Control division has quit after being arrested for drunken 
driving. 
</P>
<P>
	John G. Holl, 47, was arrested on a charge of driving while  
intoxicated Sunday night in South Orange. He ``voluntarily 
resigned,'' according to the office of Attorney General John 
Farmer. 
</P>
<P>
	Holl was paid $96,652 as director of the Alcoholic Beverage  
Control division, which regulates the liquor industry. He became 
acting director of the ABC in 1993, and was named permanent 
director two years later. 
</P>
<P>
	Holl had one drunken driving offense on his record when he was  
named to the post, having been convicted in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	His attorney could not be reached for comment Tuesday.  
  	   	
