<DOCNO> APW19990921.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 08:14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Holds Second Gold Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The Bank of England conducted its second gold sale  
today, disposing of 25 metric tons of British reserves at slightly 
more than the market price. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale, the second this year, fetched $255.75 per troy ounce.  
The opening bid price in London Tuesday morning was $255.20. 
</P>
<P>
	World gold prices have declined markedly since the Treasury  
announced its sale intention in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell about $6 to $282.40 per troy ounce on May 7, the day  
the sale was announced. The first British sale, also of 25 metric 
tons, fetched $261.20 per troy ounce. A metric ton is about 2,205 
pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury said it was selling gold to buy U.S. dollars,  
Japanese yen and the European Union's new euro currency to create a 
more balanced cash reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain intends to dispose of 125 metric tons of gold by the end  
of next year. Over the longer term, it plans to reduce British gold 
reserves from 715 metric tons to around 300 tons. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold, traditionally a haven for investors in times of turmoil,  
peaked at $875 per troy ounce in January 1980 -- a time when Soviet 
troops were moving into Afghanistan, the U.S. inflation rate was in 
double figures and oil prices were rising rapidly. 
</P>
<P>
	More recently, central banks no longer feel compelled to  
maintain large gold stockpiles to maintain confidence in their 
currencies and economies. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis Maude, Treasury spokesman for the opposition  
Conservative Party, called the sale a giveaway ``which will cost 
Britain hundreds of millions of pounds as a result of a slump in 
the world gold price.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
