<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 04:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Eyes Balkan Deployments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Last spring's NATO bombing campaign against  
Yugoslavia proved to the 19 allied nations what they already knew -- 
that there are wide gaps in military capabilities among member 
countries that must be addressed. 
</P>
<P>
	That's what the alliance's defense ministers will be doing today  
and Wednesday at their annual ``informal'' talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Separate from their twice-yearly official meetings, the informal  
talks give the ministers an opportunity to talk about a wide range 
of issues in a tranquil ambiance, free from decision-making 
pressure. It's a search for new ideas and an opportunity to push 
old ones forward. 
</P>
<P>
	With 80,000 troops in Bosnia and Kosovo, many countries feel  
they are stretched thin. Canada, with 2,700 troops in the Balkans 
and others on their way to East Timor, is an example of one country 
feeling the pinch. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, on the other hand, wants to see the Europeans  
do more and pay more. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans provided 80 percent of the air power in the  
Yugoslav campaign, which illustrated the wide disparity among the 
allies in military capabilities, equipment and the ability to 
operate effectively with other allied nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a signature year for NATO, the Kosovo campaign  
being at the forefront,'' Canadian Defense Minister Art Eggleton 
said. ``This will give us an opportunity to discuss the air 
campaign and the other aspects of the Kosovo effort ... a full 
post-mortem on this year's operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This meeting will also be the final ministerial session for  
Secretary-General Javier Solana, the 57-year-old former Spanish 
foreign minister who is moving on to the European Union, where he 
will be the 15-nation trade block's first special representative 
for foreign and security affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Solana will be replaced next month by British Defense Secretary  
George Robertson, 53, a Scot who won high praise for his strategic 
review of Britain's armed forces. Robertson is a big believer in 
the need for Europe to do more, to take on a greater share of the 
economic and military burden. 
</P>
<P>
	The Europeans say they want greater responsibility for their own  
security. They are pressing a program within NATO called the 
European Security and Defense Identity, which would enable European 
members of the alliance to take action without American 
involvement, while still using NATO assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministers will also discuss repairing relations with Russia.  
Moscow broke off military contacts with the alliance when the 
Kosovo campaign began, though Russia is now participating in the 
ground operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to help build confidence ... that NATO is not a threat  
to the Russians,'' Eggleton said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
