<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 00:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Talks To Remove Bockrath Ongoing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- As Alabama's athletics director, Bob  
Bockrath know he can't please everyone. 
</P>
<P>
	He gained support for the big things -- like hiring the popular  
choices to coach the Crimson Tide's football and basketball teams 
and for moving SEC football games out of Legion Field in 
Birmingham. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Bockrath was vilified for little things -- like  
changing the brand of soft drinks sold at Alabama events and for 
not securing enough tickets to last year's Music City Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was his latest move -- punishing rather than firing  
football coach Mike DuBose in the wake of a sexual harassment 
scandal -- that finally cost him. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama president Andrew Sorensen and Bockrath were putting the  
final touches on a deal Monday for the third-year AD's resignation, 
two school sources confirmed to The Associated Presson condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	An interim athletic director is expected to be named until a  
permanent replacement is found. 
</P>
<P>
	The resignation could come as early as this week, although  
Alabama made no formal announcement and Bockrath declined to 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Trustee Peter Lowe of Huntsville said Sorensen told the board of  
the impending deal, set in motion last week, and the trustees had 
nothing to do with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they both just thought it would be best for the  
university and for him,'' Lowe said. ``That's my understanding. 
That's what the president wanted to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Bockrath's ouster imminent, the question now turns to what  
becomes of DuBose. 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose, whose team lost 29-28 to Louisiana Tech on Saturday,  
said Monday he has heard the calls by some for his job, already 
imperiled because he admitted lying about his relationship with a 
female employee. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I don't worry about it,'' DuBose said. ``I can't worry  
about it, I can't linger on it. I come to work every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DuBose said he did not know whether his position was further  
weakened by the impending departure of Bockrath. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked Monday if he had considered resigning, DuBose, who has a  
13-13 career record at Alabama, said he hadn't. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love this university and if I was 100 percent convinced it  
was the best thing for this university, sure, I would consider 
it,'' he said. ``But I have not considered it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bockrath chose not to fire DuBose in August when the coach  
admitted to lying to him. The employee settled a sexual harassment 
claim with Alabama, and Bockrath took away the two-year contract 
extension he granted DuBose. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior tailback Shaun Alexander said much of the speculation  
about Bockrath and DuBose stemmed from the loss to Louisiana Tech. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody in these upstairs offices gets fidgety and starts  
talking and ruffling papers,'' Alexander said. ``And one thing it 
does is start rumors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bockrath's departure comes just days after university trustees  
formed a committee to oversee athletics in the three-campus Alabama 
system. While trustees said the panel had no direct control, some 
saw the move as stripping Bockrath of his power. 
</P>
<P>
	Bockrath came to Alabama from Texas Tech in June 1996. Within  
six months, Gene Stallings had resigned as football coach and 
Bockrath, following what the fans and alumni were calling for, 
hired DuBose as his replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	An Ohio native who never played for or coached with former  
Alabama coach Bear Bryant, Bockrath was viewed as an outsider to 
most fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hindsight is always 20-20,'' Bockrath said last year. ``But  
the fact that I had no connection to Coach Bryant, I didn't know 
that would affect some people as it obviously has.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
