<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers 6, Giants 5  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Eric Karros hit an RBI single with one out in  
the bottom of the ninth inning and the Los Angeles Dodgers defeated 
San Francisco 6-5 Monday night, further damaging the Giants' fading 
playoff hopes. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss left the Giants eight games behind Arizona in the NL  
West. The Diamondbacks lost to Colorado 12-7, but had their magic 
number cut to five by the Giants' loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Karros drove in four runs, and the Dodgers won on a night when  
shortstop Mark Grudzielanek and second baseman Eric Young got into 
a dugout argument. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Embree (3-1) walked Eric Young with one out in the ninth,  
and Grudzielanek greeted reliever Jerry Spradlin with a hit-and-run 
single that put runners at the corners. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Sheffield was walked intentionally to load the bases, and  
Karros lined the next pitch to left field. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedro Borbon (4-2) pitched a perfect ninth for the victory.  
</P>
<P>
	Karros had a two-run double in the fifth and Devon White added a  
sacrifice fly later in the inning for a 5-2 lead against Russ 
Ortiz. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Giants, playing the first of seven games against the  
Dodgers in a span of 11 days, rallied to tie it in the seventh 
against rookie reliever Matt Herges. Barry Bonds doubled with one 
out, Jeff Kent drove him in with a single and J.T. Snow followed 
with his 21st homer. 
</P>
<P>
	Marvin Benard opened the game with a double, advanced to third  
on a wild pitch that bounced about six feet away from catcher Todd 
Hundley, and continued home on Hundley's errant throw to third. 
</P>
<P>
	Benard led off the fifth with his 15th homer, an opposite-field  
shot that just made it inside the left-field pole and tied the 
score at 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Grudzielanek put the Dodgers ahead 2-1 in the third with his  
seventh homer of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The dugout dispute began after a steal attempt by Ellis Burks.  
Hundley, who has thrown out only 18 of 123 baserunners this season, 
made a perfect belt-high throw that easily would have retired 
Burks. 
</P>
<P>
	But neither Young nor Grudzielanek covered the bag with  
righty-swinging Rich Aurilia at the plate, and the ball sailed into 
center field as Burks continued to third. 
</P>
<P>
	Burks did not score, but Young got into an animated discussion  
in the dugout with Grudzielanek over whose responsibility it was to 
take the throw. The argument continued while the next three Dodgers 
batted, and didn't subside until Young had to take his place in the 
on-deck circle. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Mike Scioscia, who has caught more games than any Dodger in  
history and had been with the organization for almost all of the 
past 24 years, suddenly quit as manager of Triple-A Albuquerque 
``to pursue options with other major league organizations.'' The 
announcement wasn't made by the Dodgers until 10 p.m. PDT. ... Bad 
Omen Dept.: The Giants' Single-A San Jose team lost its fifth and 
deciding game of the California League championship series to the 
Dodgers' San Bernardino farm club on Sunday night. ... Burks' 
stolen base ended a string of nine unsuccessful attempts by the 
Giants. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
