<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delaware Governor To Run for Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- Gov. Thomas Carper said today he will  
seek the Democratic nomination for the Senate seat held by 
five-term incumbent William V. Roth Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	Carper, who is constitutionally barred from seeking a third term  
as governor, served five terms in Congress prior to running for his 
current post. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would take to Washington the common sense and centrist  
policies that have allowed Delaware to shine,'' Carper said at a 
press conference. ``I abhor the rancorous bickering in Washington, 
D.C. Civility must be restored in the nation's capital.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roth, 78, is chairman of the Senate Finance Committee and  
responsible for the legislation that created the Roth IRA, a 
well-known financial instrument. He has lost only once in eight 
statewide races. 
</P>
<P>
	Carper, 52, has won 10 consecutive statewide contests dating to  
his first campaign for state treasurer in 1976. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
