<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                             *Bill Guy    	
</P>
<P>
	KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) -- Bill Guy, a public radio personality known  
as a master interviewer, died Monday of cancer. He was 50. 
</P>
<P>
	Guy hosted his show on public radio station WGDT for about 15  
years and had been news director since 1985. He left the air with 
cancer in June. 
</P>
<P>
	His interview subjects included celebrities such as former  
``Tonight Show'' host Steve Allen and current Republican 
presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, Lynda; his mother, Ruth Guy; and a  
brother, Kenneth. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Willi Millowitsch    	
</P>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- Willi Millowitsch, one of Germany's  
best-known comic actors and a fixture at the famed Cologne 
carnival, died Monday. He was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Born into a Cologne family of actors, Millowitsch made his first  
stage appearance at age 5. During World War II, he toured 
Nazi-occupied France with a theater group that entertained German 
soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	His career took off in the 1950s, leading to numerous stage,  
film and TV roles. He also had pop music hits. Millowitsch's own 
theater in Cologne, which he directed until 1996, became one of 
Germany's most popular comedy stages. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Fred Roti    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Former Alderman Fred Roti, a once-powerful  
Chicago politician who was convicted of political corruption, died 
of lung cancer Monday. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI's Operation Greylord probe of City Hall corruption found  
that Roti had pocketed bribes for fixing court cases linked to 
organized crime. He was convicted of conspiracy, bribery and 
extortion by a federal jury and sentenced in 1993 to four years in 
prison. He was released in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Roti, the son of Italian immigrants, was a product of the  
notorious 1st Ward Democratic organization, long suspected of 
organized crime influence. The ward included the downtown section 
and the old Italian community around Taylor Street. 
</P>
<P>
	A diminutive man with a fondness for wearing fedoras, Roti held  
a series of city jobs, including working at the city morgue, before 
being elected alderman in 1968. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
