<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar, Gold Move Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar rose against other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold prices also were higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0383 in late European trading, down  
from $1.0396 Monday.Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro 
traded at $1.0460. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday, include  
104.09 Japanese yen, down from 107.41; 1.5448 Swiss francs, up from 
1.5424; 1.4740 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4735. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6278, up from $1.6217.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 104.70 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6295. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8837 German marks, up from 1.8813; 
6.3176 French francs, up from 6.3097; 2.1224 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.1198; 1,864.85 Italian lire, up from 1,862.51. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $259.25 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$255.10 on Monday. In Zurich the bid price was $259.65, up from 
$254.95. Gold dropped 10 cents in Hong Kong to close at $255.25. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.20 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.11. 
  	   	
</P>
