<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Floyd Leaves Public Health Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- State officials are fighting to contain a  
growing public health problem from farms, industries and sewage 
systems devastated by Hurricane Floyd and its ensuing floodwaters. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a large number of different risks out there right  
now,'' said Johanna Reese of the state Division of Environmental 
Health. ``The most immediate one we have is lack of safe drinking 
water.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have advised people in five counties to drink bottled  
water or boil tap water. It may be weeks before private wells and 
municipal water plants and lines are repaired. 
</P>
<P>
	Disease has become a growing threat from the rotting carcasses  
of millions of hogs, chickens and turkeys. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials also asked for incinerators to burn an estimated  
100,000 hogs, 2.4 million chickens and 500,000 turkeys killed. Gov. 
Jim Hunt's office estimates $1 billion in losses to agriculture, 
crops and livestock and $150 million to forestry. 
</P>
<P>
	Drinking water has been tainted by overflow from sewage plants  
and animal waste lagoons. Floodwaters are fouled by fuel, farm 
chemicals and manure. 
</P>
<P>
	The contaminated water could cause a host of gastrointestinal  
illnesses, and dehydration from severe vomiting or diarrhea could 
be fatal in children, the elderly and people with weakened immune 
systems, Reese said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of these people are down already. They're already weak,  
so they're at a greater risk,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	State health officials also recommended that residents get  
tetanus shots to protect them from infection from the filthy 
floodwater. 
</P>
<P>
	National Guard helicopters and trucks delivered clean drinking  
water to several counties Monday , while crews in Jones County 
brought in two industrial-size incinerators so workers could begin 
burning hog carcasses. 
</P>
<P>
	State agriculture commissioner Jim Graham has notified the U.S.  
Environmental Protection Agency that the state plans to use several 
insecticides to kill blowflies that feed on livestock carcasses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fly populations could become a huge public health menace,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA said more than a million gallons of wastewater, possibly  
containing chromium, spilled at the Occidental Chemical plant in 
Castle Hayne. EPA investigators were also assessing a potential 
threat of mercury contamination from a containment pond at the 
HoltraChem plant in Riegelwood. 
</P>
<P>
	On top of that, health officials warned that mosquitoes will be  
out in force because of all the standing water and could spread 
deadly encephalitis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
