<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 04:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves, Mets in Pennant Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The New York Mets doled out nearly $164 million  
to close the gap on the Atlanta Braves. In the next 10 days, 
they'll find out if it was money well spent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets are just one game behind the Braves in the NL East with  
a dozen games left in the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding more drama to an already tense race, the teams meet  
head-to-head six times, beginning tonight with the start of a 
three-game series at Turner Field. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is what you want when you've played for this long -- a  
chance to win the division,'' Mets first baseman John Olerud said. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta has won seven straight division titles, the last four by  
an average margin of 14 games. A year ago, the Braves blew away the 
second-place Mets by 18 games, knocking New York out of a wild-card 
spot by sweeping a three-game series to end the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather have a comfortable lead, but this is still fun,''  
Braves pitcher Tom Glavine said. ``It's exciting for everybody. It 
will continue to be as long as we come out on the right end of the 
stick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves haven't been in a serious pennant race, when they  
beat San Francisco by one game to win the NL West. The following 
year, Atlanta moved to the East. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking to catch up with the Braves, New York committed to  
$163.9 million in contracts after last season, keeping Mike Piazza 
and Al Leiter while adding Robin Ventura, Rickey Henderson and Orel 
Hershiser. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since the beginning of spring training, we thought making the  
playoffs or winning the division might come down to something like 
this,'' Leiter said. ``We're definitely thinking about the 
division, and I think we're a better team than we were the last 
time we played them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves won four of six games -- including a 16-0 rout at Shea  
-- when the teams met in home-and-home series in late June and early 
July. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta (92-57) and New York (91-58) are the best teams in the  
National League, so there's a strong possibility the loser in the 
division race will live to fight another day as the wild-card 
entrant. 
</P>
<P>
	That occurred two years ago, when the Braves won the East by  
nine game over Florida but were beaten in the NL championship 
series by the wild-card Marlins. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Braves are protective of their unprecedented streak of  
division titles, they would gladly trade places with the Mets if it 
meant winning a World Series title, a la the '97 Marlins. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's a choice between winning the East Division or  
winning a world championship, we'll take the world championship,'' 
third baseman Chipper Jones said. ``These games may not mean 
anything in the big picture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, the wild card is not a guaranteed consolation prize.  
The Cincinnati Reds are 3 1/2 games behind the Mets and could still 
make a run at both New York and Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``If either team should slip up and get swept,'' Jones said,  
``all of a sudden they're in a dogfight with the Reds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even with all the money spent by the Mets, Atlanta might have  
built another comfortable lead if not for an epidemic of illness 
(Andres Galarraga hasn't played because of cancer) and injuries 
(Kerry Ligtenberg, Javy Lopez, Rudy Seanez and Odalis Perez are out 
for the season). 
</P>
<P>
	Going into this critical series, the Braves could be without  
another of their top players. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Jordan, who leads the team with 106 RBIs, didn't play  
Sunday because of lingering pain in his right hand, which was 
injured when he was hit by a pitch June 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had enough guys go down,'' said Jordan, who hasn't  
homered in more than a month and doesn't know when he will play 
again. ``I almost feel like I have to be in the lineup. It's 
killing me mentally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the Mets won't have to face Atlanta's most reliable  
pitcher, Kevin Millwood, but they still get three Cy Young winners: 
John Smoltz (9-8) tonight, Glavine (11-11) on Wednesday and Greg 
Maddux (18-8) on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	New York counters with Rick Reed (10-4), Hershiser (13-10) and  
Leiter (11-12). 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to pitch against them, but it just didn't work out  
that way,'' said Millwood (18-7, 2.78 ERA). ``We have three pretty 
good guys going against them. I like our chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones sounded a bit more pessimistic if the Braves don't have  
Jordan in the lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, we're not going to mail it in. We're going to fight  
to the bitter end,'' Jones said. ``If it falls in for us, great. If 
not, we'll know every guy tried as hard as he could, and we just 
had too many injuries to overcome.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
